[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ Hello everyone and welcome to Part 1 of my Lifetime Repertoire series on the Nimzo-Indian and the Queen's Indian Defenses! For those of you who don't know me, I am Benjamin Bok, a Dutch grandmaster rated over 2600 and part of the Dutch national team. This is my first course on Chessable, and I am excited to join this great community! }
1. d4
{ One of the two most popular moves for White on move 1, the other one being  1.e4  . It is always a good idea to place a pawn in the center in the opening and White follows that principle here with  1.d4  . If White would get another move, they would love to use it to grab the full center with 2.e4.  1.d4  is generally played by players who are aiming for more of a positional game, as White is generally going to follow up with 2.c4 to grab more space in the center and on the queenside. }
1... Nf6
{ Developing the knight and preventing White from placing a second pawn in the center with  2.e4  , as now we would be able to take the pawn with  2...Nxe4  .   When the first principles of chess were developed, it was thought that Black's best way of preventing White from placing a second pawn in the center with 2.e4, was to place a pawn in the center themselves with  1...d5  .  In the early 1900s, a modern approach was developed in which Black fights for the center by controlling key squares with their pieces, instead of controlling those squares with pawns, and the Nimzo-Indian Defense is one of those modern openings. }
2. c4
{ With this move, White is aiming to play 3. Nc3 followed by 4.e4, after which White would have a great center.   White can also prepare e4 with  2.Nc3  directly, but here we can stop White from doing so with  2...d5  ,  after which the knight on c3 is considered to be misplaced, as White is unable to play c2-c4 here to exert more pressure on our center. You can learn more about this particular system in Chapter 12, where we will go through it in more depth. }
2... e6
{ Opening up the f8-a3 diagonal, so our bishop is able to develop on the next move. }
3. Nc3
{ White develops the knight and is now preparing to build a big center with 4.e4. White's other main move is  3.Nf3 ,  which delays the development of the b1-knight and keeps White's options open. In Part 2 of my Lifetime Repertoire series, we will go over the Queen's Indian Defense, which starts with  3...b6  . }
3... Bb4
{ Now we are in the Nimzo-Indian Defense, named after Aron Nimzowitsch, who popularized this opening in the early twentieth century. Nimzowitsch's idea was to prevent White from playing 4.e4 by pinning the knight on c3.  Also, we already have a slight lead in development, as White has only developed one minor piece, while we have developed two minor pieces and are ready to castle on the next move.  For White to get castled, they would still have to develop the knight on g1, play g3 or e3, and Bg2/Be2/Bd3. In some variations, we will be able to use this time to develop a strong initiative. Furthermore, we will often play ...Bxc3+ to give White doubled c-pawns, which we will attack later.  All of these ingredients combined make the Nimzo-Indian Defense a dynamic and positional weapon against 1.d4 that has stood the test of time and is considered to be one of the best defenses against 1.d4. The Nimzo-Indian Defense is also a popular opening because of its flexibility. By having played only one pawn move @@StartBracket@@2...e6@@EndBracket@@ we keep our options open as to whether we want to challenge White's center with ...c5, ...d5, ...b6, or a combination of these moves. I believe the Nimzo is a great opening at all levels for a number of reasons:  It is solid, as there are not too many variations where forgetting one move will get you in trouble, such as the Grünfeld or King's Indian Defense. It is flexible, as the pawn structure is not defined yet, such as in the Slav Defense or Queen's Gambit Declined. There is no symmetry @@StartBracket@@such as in the Exchange Slav@@EndBracket@@, which leaves plenty of play left to take over the initiative.  
All of these factors make the Nimzo-Indian Defense a great opening against both lower and higher-rated opponents. In this course, I have done my best to offer you variations that are not only holding at the highest level but also giving you the opportunity to take over the initiative.  With all that being said, let's get started. I have structured all the different setups that White can deploy into 13 chapters. I hope you will enjoy studying the variations just as much as I did and that you will win many games with this repertoire! }
*

