7... exd5 8. Rc1 Bb7
{ More accurate than  8...Re8  . After  9.Nb5  Bxd2+  10.Nxd2  ,  we are forced to play  10...c6  11.Nc3  and White has a very small edge. }
9. Bd3
{ 9.Nb5  is still a possibility, but it has lost its punch compared to the note on 8...Re8. The subtle difference could be illustrated best in the following sample line:  9...Bxd2+  10.Nxd2  a6  11.Nxc7  @@StartBracket@@  11.Nc3  is met by  11...c5  , when Black's pieces are optimally placed.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/1bN2ppp/pp3n2/3p4/3P4/4P3/PP1N1PPP/2RQKB1R b K - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Ra7  and White has to work hard to rescue the  opportunist on c7.   Instead of @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pbp2ppp/1p3n2/1N1p4/3P4/4P3/PP1N1PPP/2RQKB1R b K - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...a6  , Black can also opt for  10...c6  or even  10...c5  directly since after  11.dxc5  bxc5  12.Rxc5  , now  12...Nc6  can be played followed by a  quick ...d4, with an ongoing initiative. }
9... Re8 10. Ne5
