10... Bf8
{ We want to drop the bishop back before playing ...c5 because if we leave the bishop on b4, White could force us to give it up with a3. }
11. O-O c5 { Exerting pressure on White’s center. } 12. f4
{ Strengthening the knight on e5. } 12... Nc6
{ Exerting more pressure on the d4-pawn. Now ...cxd4 is a threat that White has to address somehow. }
13. Ne2 { Defending the pawn on d4. } 13... Rc8 14. Be1
{ The only critical move. White's idea is to play Bh4 and exert pressure on the f6-knight. }
14... Ne4
{ Moving the knight into the center before White can pin it. This move leads to massive complications, but Black is not on the worse side of them. As the lines get quite forced from here, I highly recommend you revise the moves diligently with the MoveTrainer®. }
