[Black "Rubinstein System 5.Bd3 d5 6.a3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3
{ The Rubinstein System against the Nimzo − White can adopt a lot of setups after this move, such as @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQ - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bd3  and 6.Nf3,  5.Bd3  and 6.Nge2,  5.Bd2  , and  5.Nge2  right away. We will have to respond differently to all of White's setups, but in all cases, Black gets a good game and also has a fair share of chances to take over the initiative. }
4... O-O 5. Bd3
{ White’s most popular continuation, which keeps all the options open. White can develop the g1-knight to e2 or f3, and we will respond to both moves in a similar fashion: by playing ...d5xc4 and ...c5xd4 to give White an isolated pawn on d4. White can also opt for a quick a3 to make us trade on c3, so they get the bishop pair and more pawns in the center. }
5... d5
{ Our best continuation. Often, we will aim for ...dxc4 followed by ...c5xd4, to give White an isolated pawn on d4. }
6. a3
{ This line has gained a lot in popularity recently. It leads to an interesting strategic imbalance as White will obtain the bishop pair and more pawns in the center, whereas Black has slightly more active piece play. It is imperative that we do not let White advance the pawns easily, as doing so could lead to a dangerous attack. }
6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 dxc4 8. Bxc4 c5 9. Ne2 Qc7
{ Threatening ...cxd4, which would attack the bishop on c4, so White has to move the bishop. }
10. Ba2
{ The point behind dropping the bishop back to a2 is that here it will be more difficult for us to play ...e5. Instead of that, we are going to place our bishop on the a6-f1 diagonal, which White now has left unopposed. }
10... b6 11. O-O Ba6 12. Re1
{ Played twice by Caruana. He first played this against Sevian in a classical game and later against Nepomniachtchi in a rapid game. Therefore, we must take this move seriously.  White's idea is to unpin the knight in order to play Ng3 followed by Rb1-b2, and f4 so the rook can switch over to f2. In the event of ...Na5, White will play e4, and the rook will be able to defend the d4-pawn from d2.  The computers think there are a lot of ways to play for Black, but I like my recommendation best, as it is the most straightforward. }
12... Nc6 13. Ng3 Rfd8 14. Rb1 Rd7
{ Both Sevian and Nepomniachtchi played the logical  14...Rac8  ,  but after  15.Rb2  ,  both of them struggled to come up with the right plan. I have referenced both games to showcase White's plan.  15...h6   15...Na5  16.e4  cxd4  17.cxd4  Qc3  18.Rd2  Nc4  19.Bxc4  Bxc4  20.Bb2⩲  was Caruana-Nepomniachtchi, Saint Louis 2022.  16.f4  Na5  17.e4  cxd4  18.cxd4  Qd7  was played in Caruana-Sevian, Saint Louis 2022. Here,  19.e5!  would have given Caruana a strong initiative. }
15. Rb2 Rad8
{ By putting both rooks on the d-file, ...e5 becomes an idea again. } 16. Rd2
Na5 { There are other moves, but this is the most straightforward. } 17. e4 Nc4
{ We should still delay the ...cxd4 cxd4 trade, as trading on d4 would give White the opportunity to go for a quick Bb2 and d5. }
18. Bxc4 { 18.Rd3  Ne5  19.Rd2  Nc4=  is just a repetition. } 18... Bxc4 19. e5
Ne8
{ The knight is a very important defensive piece here. White's attack is not that effective, and next up we can open the c-file with ...cxd4 cxd4 and start generating counterplay with ...Rc8. }
