[Black "Rubinstein System 5.Bd3 d5 6.a3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3
{ The Rubinstein System against the Nimzo − White can adopt a lot of setups after this move, such as @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQ - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bd3  and 6.Nf3,  5.Bd3  and 6.Nge2,  5.Bd2  , and  5.Nge2  right away. We will have to respond differently to all of White's setups, but in all cases, Black gets a good game and also has a fair share of chances to take over the initiative. }
4... O-O 5. Bd3
{ White’s most popular continuation, which keeps all the options open. White can develop the g1-knight to e2 or f3, and we will respond to both moves in a similar fashion: by playing ...d5xc4 and ...c5xd4 to give White an isolated pawn on d4. White can also opt for a quick a3 to make us trade on c3, so they get the bishop pair and more pawns in the center. }
5... d5
{ Our best continuation. Often, we will aim for ...dxc4 followed by ...c5xd4, to give White an isolated pawn on d4. }
6. a3
{ This line has gained a lot in popularity recently. It leads to an interesting strategic imbalance as White will obtain the bishop pair and more pawns in the center, whereas Black has slightly more active piece play. It is imperative that we do not let White advance the pawns easily, as doing so could lead to a dangerous attack. }
6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 dxc4 8. Bxc4 c5 9. Nf3
{ This is Swiercz's main recommendation against the Nimzo in his 1.d4 Chessable repertoire. }
9... Qc7 { X-raying the bishop on c4 and thus forcing White to retreat it. }
10. Be2 b6 11. Bb2 cxd4
{ Often we should delay this capture, but here it is important to start with this move.   If we start with  11...Ba6?!  ,  White has  12.c4  cxd4  13.Nxd4  ,  which gives White a small edge. The point is that  13...Bxc4  runs into  14.Qc2  ,  pinning the bishop on c4.  14...b5  @@StartBracket@@  14...Rc8?!  15.Rc1  only gives White a better version.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn3rk1/p1q2ppp/4pn2/1p6/2bN4/P3P3/1BQ1BPPP/R3K2R w KQ - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Nxb5  Qa5+  16.Qc3  Qxc3+  17.Bxc3⩲  and White has a nagging advantage in the endgame. }
12. cxd4 Ba6
{ Trading off one pair of bishops is often a good way to neutralize the opponent's bishop pair. }
13. O-O Bxe2 14. Qxe2 Nbd7 15. e4 Rfc8
{ Slightly more accurate than  15...Rac8  , as the rook will often be quite useful on the queenside in case we start pushing our pawns on that side of the board. }
16. Rfc1 Qb7 17. Re1 b5
{ In many cases, we can just create a passed pawn on the queenside with ...a5 and ...b4. Furthermore, we can double the rooks with ...Rc4 and ...Rac8. Black's position is solid and we have sufficient counterplay to compensate for White's center. }
