[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Classical Variation 4.Qc2 d5 5.a3 − 7.cxd5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2
{ The Classical Variation of the Nimzo. The idea behind this move is twofold: White enables the recapture on c3 with the queen and can therefore keep the structure intact. Furthermore, with this move, White also enables the move e4. }
4... d5
{ I recommend this move, as I would like to avoid the lines starting with  4...O-O  5.e4  . This gives White the additional option of @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/1bPP4/2N5/PPQ1PPPP/R1B1KBNR w KQkq d6 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.cxd5  , but those lines actually work out quite nicely for Black, as I will offer you a combative antidote. }
5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 O-O
{ White has a lot of positional trumps: the bishop pair, and the one bishop we have is somewhat blocked in by our pawns. However, the drawback of White's play is that our opponent is quite far behind in development and it will take quite a long time before White will get castled. Because of this, it is of utmost importance that we open up the center quickly and try to strike before White can get fully developed. }
7. cxd5
{ Carlsen played this in a recent blitz game against Caruana. White's idea is to trade on d5 before Black will trade on c4. }
7... Ne4
{ We play this move first so White cannot pin our knight on f6 with Bg5. } 8.
Qc2 exd5 { Regaining the pawn and bolstering our knight on e4. } 9. Bf4 Nc6
{ Usually, it is not advisable to place the knight in front of the c7-pawn in these structures, but we want to develop quickly here. }
10. e3 Re8
{ By x-raying the king on e1, we bring ...Nxd4 ideas in the position. } 11. Nf3
{ Defending against the aforementioned ...Nxd4 ideas. If White has the time to consolidate here, they could get an edge due to the bishop pair and slightly better structure. Therefore, we should act quickly. }
11... g5 12. Bg3 { Practically White’s only move. } 12... g4
{ By attacking the knight on f3, we try to bring the ...Nxd4 ideas back in position. }
13. Ne5
{ White’s best move, as this closes the e-file and makes sure that Black does not have ...Nxd4. }
13... Nxe5
{ Of course, we should trade White’s active knight on e5 and try to keep our initiative going. }
14. dxe5 h5
{ We play this move so that in the event of ...Nxg3 hxg3 and ...Rxe5, our rook on e5 protects the pawn on h5. }
15. f3 Nxg3 16. hxg3 Rxe5
{ White certainly has compensation, but we are up a pawn and White's attack is not too dangerous. }
