1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2
{ The Classical Variation of the Nimzo. The idea behind this move is twofold: White enables the recapture on c3 with the queen and can therefore keep the structure intact. Furthermore, with this move, White also enables the move e4. }
4... d5
{ I recommend this move, as I would like to avoid the lines starting with  4...O-O  5.e4  . This gives White the additional option of @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/1bPP4/2N5/PPQ1PPPP/R1B1KBNR w KQkq d6 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.cxd5  , but those lines actually work out quite nicely for Black, as I will offer you a combative antidote. }
5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 O-O
{ White has a lot of positional trumps: the bishop pair, and the one bishop we have is somewhat blocked in by our pawns. However, the drawback of White's play is that our opponent is quite far behind in development and it will take quite a long time before White will get castled. Because of this, it is of utmost importance that we open up the center quickly and try to strike before White can get fully developed. }
7. Bg5 h6
{ After careful consideration, I have chosen to recommend this move.   7...dxc4  and  7...c5  are also possible but lead to extremely sharp variations where Black could be in big trouble if a line is forgotten or if Black is surprised by a dangerous novelty. The text, however, is rock-solid and provides a comfortable path to equality. }
8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. Nf3 dxc4 10. Qxc4 Nc6
{ The point behind this move is to play ...e5 quickly. } 11. Qc3
{ Stopping the ...e5 push from Black. } 11... Re8
{ Reinforcing the ...e5 push. White cannot stop us from playing ...e5 here but can try to anticipate it. }
12. Rd1
{ The only critical move, making sure that after  12...e5  13.d5  , Black does not have  13...Nd4  . }
12... e5 13. d5 Nb8
{ Our knight is forced back, but we will activate it again later. Here, and on the next couple of moves, White can take the pawn on c7. However, by doing so, White could face a strong initiative and therefore this is not something we should be worried about.  Of course, we should know how to respond in case White does decide to take the c7-pawn now or later on, which is why I covered the capture on the next couple of moves in the relevant chapter. }
14. e3 Bf5
{ 14...Bg4  is also possible. This leads to more forcing variations. I prefer  14...Bf5  , as it leaves more play in the position and Black has the potential to outplay White, which is what happened in the game between Hans Niemann and Fabiano Caruana at the 2022 US Championship. }
15. Be2 Nd7 16. O-O Rac8
{ Finally, we do defend the pawn on c7. This move also enables Black to play ...c6 in many positions. For the in-depth analysis, see the corresponding chapter. }
