1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2
{ The Classical Variation of the Nimzo. The idea behind this move is twofold: White enables the recapture on c3 with the queen and can therefore keep the structure intact. Furthermore, with this move, White also enables the move e4. }
4... d5
{ I recommend this move, as I would like to avoid the lines starting with  4...O-O  5.e4  . This gives White the additional option of @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/1bPP4/2N5/PPQ1PPPP/R1B1KBNR w KQkq d6 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.cxd5  , but those lines actually work out quite nicely for Black, as I will offer you a combative antidote. }
5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4
{ Played by a couple of strong players, including Mamedyarov and Caruana. However, there are not many lines we have to know here and Black is completely fine in all of them. }
6... c5
{ Since White has not played @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2ppp/5n2/3p4/1b1P4/2N5/PPQ1PPPP/R1B1KBNR w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bg5  and pinned our knight, it is easier to strike in the center now. }
7. dxc5 Nc6 8. e3 O-O 9. Nf3 d4
{ Using our lead in development to try to break open the center. } 10. O-O-O
Bxc5 11. exd4 Bd6
{ Of course, taking the pawn on d4 is poisonous due to the pin on the d-file. }
12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. a3
{ Preventing ...Nb4 since, for instance, a careless move like  13.Kb1  runs straight into  13...Nb4  followed by ...Bf5+ and the game is over.   The direct  13.Nb5  is also not something to worry about since after  13...Qb8  , we maintain  similar developing ideas: ...Be6, ...Rc8, while the knight on b5 can always be pushed back with ...a6. }
13... Be6
{ Black has sufficient compensation for the pawn, as our king on g8 is much safer than White's king on c1 or b1. Furthermore, the pawn on d4 can become weak, and White might end up giving it back to relieve some of Black's pressure.   13...Bg4  has also been played in a couple of games, but the text is the most accurate. }
14. Kb1 Na5 { Threatening ...Bb3. } 15. d5
{ It's in White's best interest to give back the pawn to stop Black's initiative. With this move, White also hopes to create a small initiative, but with accurate play, we have it covered.   In case of  15.Qd3  , we can play  15...g6  , and the queen has an issue again, while @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/pp3ppp/3qbn2/n7/3P4/P1N2N2/1PQ2PPP/1K1R1B1R w - - 3 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Qa4  can be simply met with  15...b6  or even  15...Qd8  since after  16.d5  Nxd5  17.Nxd5  Bxd5=  , White cannot profit from the pin on the d-file. }
15... Nxd5 16. Nxd5 Bxd5
{ We should not be worried about the pin along the d-file, as White does not have an effective way to increase the pressure on the d5-bishop. }
17. Bd3 g6 18. Be4 Bxe4 19. Qxe4 Qc7
{ Improving on the game Caruana-Dominguez, lichess.org 2020. We keep an eye on the e5-square, so if White were to put the knight there, we can put pressure on it right away with ...Rfe8.   After  19...Qb6?!  20.Ne5↑  ,  Caruana had a slight initiative. }
