[Black "Kasparov Variation 4.Nf3 − 6.e3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3
{ The Kasparov Variation. The main idea behind this move is to see how Black will react and then proceed most appropriately to Black's response. }
4... O-O
{ Black has a lot of moves, but I like this one the most, as it is simple and flexible. }
5. Bg5
{ Now that Black has castled, this move gains in strength, as playing ...h6 and ...g5 has somewhat lost its appeal since that would always weaken the black king.   If White plays  5.e3  ,  we will play  5...d5  and transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  O-O  5.Nf3  d5  .   5.Bd2  is also likely to transpose to the 4.e3 system, as here we play  5...d5  and White's best move is  6.e3  .   In case White plays  5.Qc2  ,  we will play  5...d5  and transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qc2  d5  5.Nf3  O-O  . }
5... c5 { We should exert pressure on White's center as quickly as possible. }
6. e3
{ Played three times by Jeffery Xiong against very strong opposition with good results @@StartBracket@@2/3@@EndBracket@@. However, with correct play, the path to equality is quite straightforward.   6.Qb3  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQ - 4 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qb3  c5  6.Bg5  . }
6... cxd4
{ This will almost always be our follow-up after ...c5. The point is that in case of a potential exd4, we want to play ...d5xc4 and give White an isolated pawn on d4. }
7. exd4 h6
{ It’s always a good idea to meet an early Bg5 with this move. We push White’s bishop back a bit, make some luft for the king, and we can potentially break the pin with ...g5. Furthermore, we should not be worried at all about White trading on f6, as our queen gets activated and we get the bishop pair advantage. }
8. Bh4 d5
{ Getting our fair share of the center. Furthermore, we want to take on c4 potentially and give White an isolated pawn. }
9. Rc1
{ A clever move. White is delaying the development of the light-squared bishop so that in the event of ...dxc4, White can recapture with the bishop on c4 in one go, gaining a tempo thanks to Rc1. }
9... Nc6
{ We want to wait for White to move the bishop before trading on c4, so first, we should develop the knight. }
10. a3 { Forcing us to make a decision with our dark-squared bishop. } 10...
Be7
{ The best move, not conceding the bishop pair, and neutralizing White’s pin on the h4-d8 diagonal. }
11. c5
{ The only way to play for an advantage − without this move, we will take on c4 soon and give White an isolated pawn on d4. If White is able to consolidate here with Be2/d3 and O-O, White will have an advantage due to the space advantage on the queenside and our passive bishop on c8. Therefore, we should act quickly. }
11... Ne4
{ Activating the knight and offering the trade of bishops so our queen gets on a slightly better square. }
12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. Be2 Rd8
{ Preparing the ...e5 break by defending the pawn on d5 once more. } 14. b4
{ This is what Xiong played against So in their chess.com Global Championship match. }
14... e5
{ This move might seem somewhat unnatural, as we give ourselves an isolated pawn on d5, but it is absolutely necessary that we break up White’s center and free our light-squared bishop. }
15. Nxe5
{ The only way for White to take the pawn.  15.dxe5?  runs into  15...Nxc3  16.Rxc3  d4  and Black gets a crushing initiative in the center. }
15... Nxe5 16. dxe5 a5
{ After  16...Nxc3  17.Rxc3  d4  18.Rg3  ,  White was a little bit better in the aforementioned game Xiong-So, chess.com 2022.   Also, the greedy  16...Qxe5  gets punished by  17.Nxe4  Qxe4  18.O-O  , when Black is left with a  weakness on d5 and without counterattacking prospects on White's queenside pawn chain.  For instance, trying to create counterplay now with  18...a5  can be simply met by  19.b5±  , which is not an option after the text move, @@StartFEN@@r1br2k1/pp2qpp1/7p/2PpP3/1P2n3/P1N5/4BPPP/2RQK2R b K - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16...a5  . }
17. O-O
{ White’s best move is just to complete development and get the king out of the center. }
17... axb4 18. axb4 Nxc3
{ It is most accurate to trade the knights ourselves. After  18...Qxe5  , White has  19.Nxe4  Qxe4  20.Qd2  with a small  edge, as Bf3 is coming next. }
19. Rxc3 Qxe5
{ This position is a lot more comfortable for Black than what Black got in the Xiong-So game. The opening of the a-file has made White's pawn on b4 a clear target, and Black can always use the a-file to generate counterplay. }
