[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Kasparov Variation 4.Nf3 − 6.Rc1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3
{ The Kasparov Variation. The main idea behind this move is to see how Black will react and then proceed most appropriately to Black's response. }
4... O-O
{ Black has a lot of moves, but I like this one the most, as it is simple and flexible. }
5. Bg5
{ Now that Black has castled, this move gains in strength, as playing ...h6 and ...g5 has somewhat lost its appeal since that would always weaken the black king.   If White plays  5.e3  ,  we will play  5...d5  and transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  O-O  5.Nf3  d5  .   5.Bd2  is also likely to transpose to the 4.e3 system, as here we play  5...d5  and White's best move is  6.e3  .   In case White plays  5.Qc2  ,  we will play  5...d5  and transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qc2  d5  5.Nf3  O-O  . }
5... c5 { We should exert pressure on White's center as quickly as possible. }
6. Rc1
{ With this move, White enables the recapture with the rook on c3, keeping the structure intact.   6.Qb3  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQ - 4 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qb3  c5  6.Bg5  . }
6... cxd4 7. Nxd4
{ Taking with the queen on d4 allows us to develop with tempo:  7.Qxd4  Nc6  and the queen has to move again. }
7... h6
{ As we will often see in this opening, ...h6 will almost always be a good way to meet Bg5. We do not mind the trade on f6, and the inclusion of ...h6 and Bh4 favors us somewhat. We will have an escape square for our king, and we can potentially break the pin with ...g5 as well. }
8. Bh4 d5
{ It is a good idea to strike in the center, as White is still quite far from getting castled. }
9. cxd5
{ This leads to the sharpest lines.   9.a3?  gets punished by  9...Bxc3+  10.Rxc3  e5  11.Nb3  d4  and Black has a significant advantage. }
9... g5
{ Pushing White's bishop back to g3, so we can take on d5 with our queen, without White being able to play Bxf6 and open up our king. }
10. Bg3 Qxd5
{ Developing the queen and attacking the pawn on a2. White's best attempt for an advantage is to sacrifice the pawn to try to launch an initiative on the kingside. }
11. e3 Qxa2
{ Now that we have captured the pawn on a2, we also threaten to take on b2, after which White will lose the knight on c3 as well. }
12. Bd3
{ With this move, White sacrifices another pawn, and with that, also the knight on c3. We have to accept both sacrifices, and with accurate play, Black is fine. }
12... Qxb2
{ Taking another pawn and now we are also threatening to take the knight on c3. }
13. O-O
{ Since there is no good way to defend the knight, the best continuation is to just sacrifice it. Fortunately for the White players, they get plenty of threats. }
13... Bxc3
{ We have to take the knight since otherwise, White has too much play for just two pawns. }
14. Rc2 Qb4 15. Nb5 e5
{ We have to give up the bishop, as Bd6 was a big threat from White. } 16. Rxc3
Nc6 17. f4
{ This position is a mess. White has a lead in development and Black's king is somewhat weakened. On the other hand, White's pieces are quite loose and Black has a lot of defensive resources. The computers say pretty much anything is fine for Black, but that also makes it confusing. I recommend the following line to make things more clear-cut. }
17... a6 18. Rb3
{ Moving the rook so the knight can escape the a6-pawn's attack. } 18... Qe7
{ Bringing the queen back to the defense. } 19. fxg5 Ng4
{ Moving the knight and simultaneously threatening ...Nxe3, which would fork the queen and the rook. }
20. Nd6 Nxe3 21. Bh7+
{ This simplifies matters. White sacrifices the bishop to be able to capture the knight on e3 and get rid of the fork that way. }
21... Kxh7 22. Rxe3 Qxg5
{ Black will also develop the light-squared bishop in the foreseeable future and is fine here. The game Li-Xu, Hangzhou 2022 ended in a draw. }
