[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Nimzo-Indian 4.f3 − 7.Bd2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3
{ The idea behind this move is quite simple − White wants to build a big center by going e4 quickly. Subsequently, White often tries to use the center to go for an attack on the kingside.  White players usually choose this move when they have aggressive intentions as opposed to trying to get a small edge and playing a risk-free game. This is because Black has lots of different ways to respond to this line.  I am going to recommend a line that has not been played yet at the top level, but it solves Black's problems and gives us the double-edged game that we are looking for. }
4... c5
{ Challenging White's center right away. Furthermore, this move enables ...Qa5, which exerts pressure on the c3-knight. }
5. d5
{ Practically the only move if White wants to keep their hopes of an advantage and not get a worse position immediately.   If White plays  5.a3  , we will transpose to the Sämisch Variation after  5...Bxc3+  6.bxc3  . }
5... b5
{ Exerting pressure on the c4-pawn in typical Benko style. White's best choice is to decline any immediate pawn sacrifices, as Black will get a big initiative.   5...d6  is also fine, as after  6.e4  b5  ,  we transpose to the main line. }
6. e4 { Defending the pawn on c4. } 6... d6
{ Stopping White's e5 push. Here White has a lot of options, but against all of them, we get a good game and also get our chances to take over the initiative. }
7. Bd2 { Unpinning the knight on c3, so now Nxb5 becomes a threat. } 7... a6
{ Defending the pawn on b5 and insisting on a pawn sacrifice. It is still  White's best choice to not accept the pawn sacrifice. }
8. a4
{ Attacking the pawn on b5 once more. In case White opts for  8.a3  instead, the tempered  8...Ba5  9.b4  Bb6  is the way to go since  9...cxb4  10.axb4  Bxb4  runs straight into  11.Nxb5  , which is something to avoid. }
8... exd5 { Going for a line that has not been played yet at the top level. }
9. cxd5 bxa4
{ This has been played in some correspondence games, but only once at the GM level. White has two options here:  Make logical developing moves and just play a Benoni-type position. Grab a pawn in a forcing variation.  
In either case, Black is fine, and especially if White goes for the first option, we will have our chances to outplay White. If White decides to go for the second option, there are different ways to develop their pieces:  White can play Nge2-g3 followed by Be2. In this case, we will play ...h5-h4 since the knight does not have a comfortable square to go to. White can also play Bd3 followed by Nge2. In this case, we will play ...Nbd7-e5. }
10. Qxa4+ Nbd7
{ White can still change their mind here if they do not want to go pawn-grabbing and continue development. In that case, White has to decide whether they would develop the g1-knight from e2 to g3 or from h3 to f2. }
11. Qc6 Rb8 { Now, the next couple of moves are forced. } 12. Bxa6
{ This is the pawn White can grab.  12.Qxd6?  is a bad idea. } 12... O-O 13.
Bxc8 Ne5 { Gaining a tempo on the white queen and eyeing the d3-square. } 14.
Qa6
{ The two correspondence games that reached this position continued with  14...Rxc8  and Black held in both of those. The subsequent positions are still quite complicated and require some accuracy from Black. However, Black can also recapture with the queen, which is a somewhat easier path to equality.  Both options are equally good and I will therefore leave the choice to you as to whether you want to recapture with the queen or the rook. I would recommend taking with the rook if you are looking for a fighting game, and I would recommend taking with the queen if you want to keep things simple and solid. }
14... Qxc8 15. Qxc8 Rfxc8
{ Black has sufficient compensation for the pawn. All of our pieces are active, while White is not fully developed yet. }
16. Ke2
{ Stopping ...Nd3+, which would win the pawn back immediately.  16.Nh3  Nd3+  17.Ke2  Nxb2  would transpose to the 17.Nh3 variation. }
16... Nc4
{ Here White has to decide whether to give the pawn back and free the pieces or hang on to the pawn and remain somewhat cramped. }
17. Nh3 Nxb2 18. Rhc1 Nc4
{ The position is equal, and there is simply too little material left for any side to create anything. }
