[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Jobava London 3.Bf4 c5 4.e4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3
{ By playing Nc3, White prepares the move 3.e4. As we don't want to give White the full center, we have to play ...d5. }
2... d5
{ Structurally speaking, White's knight is misplaced on c3. It stops White from exerting pressure on Black's center with c2-c4, and it also prevents White from strengthening their own center with c2-c3. However, White usually plays for quick development in this opening. }
3. Bf4
{ The Jobava London. This has become a popular weapon in rapid and blitz games, as White has quick development and many traps. However, with accurate play, Black gets a good game. }
3... c5
{ Challenging White’s center right away. I like this move, as it is the most direct. }
4. e4
{ This is Hans Niemann's recommendation in his Chessable course on the Jobava London. It leads to direct complications, so it is important that we familiarize ourselves with the lines. }
4... cxd4 5. Qxd4 Nc6 6. Bb5 Bd7
{ Essentially, forcing White to give up the bishop pair, which gives us a long-term asset. If we survive the next few moves, which we will, Black is likely to have good prospects. }
7. Bxc6 Bxc6 8. e5 Nd7 9. e6
{ White has to go for this pawn sacrifice. If White does not play this move, we will just continue with ...e6, and Black has a very comfortable French thanks to the bishop pair. }
9... fxe6 10. Nf3
{ The point behind White's play is that it is not easy for us to develop, as we currently cannot play ...g6, and ...e5 is also firmly under control. }
10... Qb6
{ Offering the queen trade in order to relieve some of White's grip on our position. }
11. Qd2 d4 { It is important to give the pawn back to liberate our pieces. }
12. Nxd4
{ 12.Qxd4  Bxf3=  and after  13.Qxb6  ,  either recapture followed by ...g6 is fine for Black. }
12... Bxg2 13. Ndb5 e5
{ Attacking the bishop and blocking the h2-b8 diagonal, so White does not have Nc7+ anymore. }
14. Be3 Qc6 15. Rg1 a6
{ We're still a pawn up, and Black is certainly not worse in the complications. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Jobava London 3.Bf4 c5 4.e3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3
{ By playing Nc3, White prepares the move 3.e4. As we don't want to give White the full center, we have to play ...d5. }
2... d5
{ Structurally speaking, White's knight is misplaced on c3. It stops White from exerting pressure on Black's center with c2-c4, and it also prevents White from strengthening their own center with c2-c3. However, White usually plays for quick development in this opening. }
3. Bf4
{ The Jobava London. This has become a popular weapon in rapid and blitz games, as White has quick development and many traps. However, with accurate play, Black gets a good game. }
3... c5
{ Challenging White’s center right away. I like this move, as it is the most direct. }
4. e3
{ The calmer approach. White intends to recapture on d4 with the e-pawn and play a Carlsbad structure. }
4... cxd4 5. exd4 a6
{ Stopping Nb5. Structurally speaking, Black is doing very well, as White's knight is misplaced on c3. White has to try to do something quickly, as otherwise, they are just worse if we get ...Nc6 and ...Bg4/f5 in. }
6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Ne5
{ The only critical move. After any other move, we develop our bishop to g4 or f5 and get a very comfortable position. White further activates the knight and also creates the positional threat of Nxc6, as ...bxc6 would be slightly detrimental to our pawn structure. }
7... Bd7
{ Therefore, we play this move so we can recapture with the bishop on c6 and keep our pawn structure intact. Again, if White were to play slowly here, Black is completely fine. So every top game from this position continued with g4. }
8. g4
{ If White does not play this move, we will just play ...e6 next, with a very comfortable position. }
8... e6 9. g5 Nxe5 10. Bxe5 Ng8
{ This move might look passive, but we are rerouting the knight via e7 to c6, from where it would exert pressure on the e5-bishop. Furthermore, we are going to play ...h6 quickly, as White is somewhat overextended on the kingside and White does not have a comfortable way to keep the structure intact on that side of the board. }
11. h4 h6 12. Qh5
{ White's best move, as this is the only way to keep the structure intact. Note that g6 can always be comfortably met with ...f6. }
12... Ne7
{ The knight is headed to g6, from where it would not only exert pressure on the e5-bishop but also defend the rook on h8, thus enabling the move ...hxg5. }
13. Bd3 { Stopping the knight from going to g6. } 13... Nc6
{ So we go to this square to exert pressure on the bishop on e5. } 14. O-O-O
Nxe5 15. dxe5 Bb4 16. Ne2 Qe7
{ Black is already somewhat for choice. We have the bishop pair, and our king will be perfectly safe after we castle queenside in the foreseeable future. }
