[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6 3.Bf4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Bf4
{ This move has been played recently by a lot of strong grandmasters. The idea is to meet  3...Bb4+  with  4.Nd2  and later try to get the bishop pair without allowing Black to double White's pawns as we will often do in the Nimzo. }
3... d5
{ Placing a pawn in the center is rarely a bad idea, and this is no exception. }
4. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Usually, we would recapture with the pawn on d5, but here it’s good to recapture with the knight to gain a tempo, as we attack White’s bishop on f4. }
5. Bg3 c5 { Challenging White’s center right away. } 6. e4
{ This is how Carlsen, Niemann, and Nihal continued in this position, and it is arguably the critical continuation of the 3.Bf4 variation. This move involves a pawn sacrifice, but White hopes to get plenty of compensation due to the active pieces.   After  6.dxc5  Bxc5  7.Nd2  Nc6  ,  we will continue with ...O-O and ...f6 followed by ...e5, to neutralize White's bishop on g3, and Black has a comfortable position. }
6... Nf6 7. Nd2 Qxd4
{ The most accurate way to take the pawn. Ding was the only one to play this way in his Speed Chess Championship match against Nihal Sarin. }
8. Ngf3 Qd8 9. e5
{ This is the point of White's play. White hopes that the pawn on e5 will restrict Black's pieces and that their space advantage on the kingside will give them attacking chances. White certainly has compensation for the pawn, but with accurate play, Black is certainly not worse, and we will also get our chances to get an advantage.   The slower  9.Qb3  , planning to castle queenside, doesn't interfere with our development so we can just continue with  9...Be7  10.O-O-O  O-O  11.Nc4  Nbd7  12.Nd6  a6  , when Black has a clear-cut plan  now with ...b5, while White still has to figure out how to attack us on the kingside. }
9... Nd5 10. Bd3 Be7
{ Ding followed up here with ...Bd7-c6 and ...Nd7. He quickly got a good position and won in the game Nihal-Ding, chess.com 2022.   In case White starts hostilities on the kingside with  11.h4  , we should probably play the wise  11...Bd7  as planned, instead of  11...O-O  . Following  12.Bxh7+  Kxh7  13.Ng5+  Kh6  14.Qc2  g6  15.h5  Kg7  16.Nxf7!  Rxf7  17.Qxg6+  Kh8  @@StartBracket@@  17...Kf8  loses to  18.h6  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbq3k/pp2br2/4p1Q1/2pnP2P/8/6B1/PP1N1PP1/R3K2R w KQ - 0 18@@EndFEN@@  18.Qxf7  , the position is too messy to be worth the trouble. Developing first and waiting for White to reveal their cards is a better strategy. }
