[White "1) Rubinstein System 4.e3 O-O − 5th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "Rubinstein System 4.e3 O-O 5.Nge2 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3
{ The Rubinstein System against the Nimzo − White can adopt a lot of setups after this move, such as @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQ - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bd3  and 6.Nf3,  5.Bd3  and 6.Nge2,  5.Bd2  , and  5.Nge2  right away. We will have to respond differently to all of White's setups, but in all cases, Black gets a good game and also has a fair share of chances to take over the initiative. }
4... O-O 5. Ne2
{ This was Rubinstein's initial idea behind 4.e3. White wants to play 6.a3 and be able to recapture on c3 with the knight. However, nowadays, this line is not considered to be critical and Black gets a good game quite easily. }
5... d5 6. a3
{ Trading the bishop for the knight on c3 will give White a clear advantage due to the bishop pair, so we will have to drop our bishop back. White should play this move before trading on d5, as it pushes our bishop to the more passive e7-square.   6.cxd5  right away is quite toothless, as after  6...exd5⇆  , we can always retreat to the more active d6-square in case of a3. }
6... Be7
{ Since we do not want to trade on c3 and  6...Bd6  runs into  7.c5  , this is the best retreating square for our bishop.  Now, the c4-pawn is currently under attack, and White has to decide how to address that issue. }
7. cxd5
{ White’s most popular move and the easiest way to deal with the hanging c4-pawn. }
7... exd5
{ After the trade on d5, we are now in the Carlsbad structure. Given the fact that White’s dark-squared bishop is stuck behind the pawn chain and not on an active square, such as g5 or f4, we have a comfortable game here. }
8. Nf4
{ White’s most popular move. The knight is best placed on this square and White will follow up with Bd3, O-O, and f3. }
8... c6
{ Strengthening our pawn on d5 to prepare ...Nbd7. Next up, we are going to play ...Re8, followed by ...Nbd7-f8. }
9. Bd3 { The most active square for White’s light-squared bishop. } 9... Re8
{ The start of our plan. The rook is well placed on the e-file, as it will make it more difficult for White to get f3 and e4 in.   Another plan in this position is to go  9...Na6  followed by Nc7-e6. However, I like the knight maneuver to f8, as it keeps our options open − sometimes we want to move the knight to g6. }
10. O-O Nbd7 { Continuing with our plan − the knight is headed to f8. } 11. f3
{ With this move, White is aiming to build a big center with e3-e4. However, we are just in time to prevent that. }
11... Nf8
{ Moving the knight out of the queen’s way and thus stopping the e3-e4 idea, as after  12.e4?!  dxe4  13.fxe4?  ,  the pawn on d4 is hanging:  13...Qxd4-+  .   The results in practical games prove that we also have our chances to take over the initiative. We can further improve the position with either ...Ng6 or ...Ne6, or moves such as ...Bd6 to open up the rook on e8. }
