{ Black has a great game, as White's dark-squared bishop is passive and the c4-pawn is quite weak too.   10.Ng3  Bxc4  11.Nxe4  Nxe4  12.Bxe4  Nc6  13.Bd3  Na5  was seen in Gupta-Gukesh, New Delhi 2022, when the control of the light squares can be increased further with ...d5. Black is better already.   Defending c4 with  10.Qb3  is possible, and White can even win a pawn in certain lines, but that will only yield a powerful initiative for us. Since the pawns on the c-file are doubled, the material advantage is only an illusion,  while the king on e1 still needs to get out of the center too.   After  10...Nbd7  11.Ng3  , it is perhaps a matter of taste on how to continue.  11...b5  seems like an interesting choice and following  12.Qxb5  Rb8  13.Qc6  Rb6  14.Qa4  , the adventurers might consider  14...Rxb1  , but  14...h5  is already pressuring White. Of course, the pawn on e4 is taboo since  15.Nxe4?  Rxb1!  16.Nxf6+  Qxf6  17.Rxb1  Qg6  is game over for White.  Additionally, @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pppn1ppp/3pbn2/8/2PPp3/PQP1P1N1/5PPP/RBB1K2R b KQ - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Nb6  can also be played since after  12.d5  Bd7  13.Nxe4  Nxe4  14.Bxe4  f5  , White's weaknesses will start to be exploited.  The bishop on c1 is not a knight to jump over the wall of pawns, while Black can continue to increase the pressure with ideas such as ...Ba4 followed by rerouting the knight via d7, or ...Na4-c5, ...Qh4, and ...Rae8. Black is still a pawn down, but the initiative plays a bigger role. We are just better. }
