[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3
{ The Rubinstein System against the Nimzo − White can adopt a lot of setups after this move, such as @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQ - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bd3  and 6.Nf3,  5.Bd3  and 6.Nge2,  5.Bd2  , and  5.Nge2  right away. We will have to respond differently to all of White's setups, but in all cases, Black gets a good game and also has a fair share of chances to take over the initiative. }
4... O-O 5. a3 { Played on numerous occasions by Caruana and Grischuk. } 5...
Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 d6
{ We should go for a quick ...e5-e4, which not only prevents White from building up a big center but also blocks in White's dark-squared bishop. }
7. f3
{ This is the critical continuation and what Caruana played three times. The idea is to be able to meet  7...e5  with  8.e4  ,  when White prevents Black from playing ...e4. Black has multiple ways to get a fine double-edged game. I recommend the following line: }
7... Nc6 8. Bd3 b6 9. e4
{ 9.Ne2  gives us the time to unfold our typical plan with  9...Ba6  followed by ...Na5, adding pressure on the c4-pawn. }
9... Qe8 { Planning to meet Bg5 with ...Nd7. } 10. Bg5 Nd7
{ Next up, we can play ...Ba6 and ...Na5 to put pressure on White's pawn on c4. Furthermore, we always have ...f6 to push back White's bishop on g5 and to solidify the kingside and the center. Black has a fine game and also has a chance to outplay White from this position. }
