[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Rubinstein System 4.e3 O-O − 5th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "Rubinstein System 4.e3 O-O 5.a3 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3
{ The Rubinstein System against the Nimzo − White can adopt a lot of setups after this move, such as @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQ - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bd3  and 6.Nf3,  5.Bd3  and 6.Nge2,  5.Bd2  , and  5.Nge2  right away. We will have to respond differently to all of White's setups, but in all cases, Black gets a good game and also has a fair share of chances to take over the initiative. }
4... O-O 5. a3 { Played on numerous occasions by Caruana and Grischuk. } 5...
Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 d6
{ We should go for a quick ...e5-e4, which not only prevents White from building up a big center but also blocks in White's dark-squared bishop. }
7. Ne2
{ With this move, White's plan is to play Ng3, Bd3, O-O, and e4, to try to launch an initiative on the kingside. I have covered such plans at length in the Sämisch chapter.  Generally, we will aim to challenge White's weakened pawn structure with ...c5, ...Nc6, ...b6, and ...Ba6, followed by ...Na5 to attack the weak c4-pawn. }
7... c5 8. Ng3 Nc6
{ It is important to start with ...c5 and ...Nc6, as this exerts more pressure on the d4-pawn and will make it more difficult for White to get e3-e4 in. }
9. Bd3 b6 { We continue with our plan − the bishop is coming out to a6 next. }
10. O-O Ba6
{ It is important to play this move first, and delay ...Na5, as that would release the pressure on White's d4-pawn and White would be able to play e4.  I already prefer Black in this position, as the c4-pawn is quite weak and it will be difficult for White to get an initiative on the kingside. Next, we are going to play ...Rc8 and ...Na5 and sooner or later the c4-pawn is going to fall. }
