[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Rubinstein System 4.e3 O-O 5.Bd2 & 5.Nf3"]
[Black "Rubinstein System 4.e3 O-O 5.Nf3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3
{ The Rubinstein System against the Nimzo − White can adopt a lot of setups after this move, such as @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQ - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bd3  and 6.Nf3,  5.Bd3  and 6.Nge2,  5.Bd2  , and  5.Nge2  right away. We will have to respond differently to all of White's setups, but in all cases, Black gets a good game and also has a fair share of chances to take over the initiative. }
4... O-O 5. Nf3 d5 6. Bd2
{ This line has become quite critical in recent years. White's idea is to delay the development of the light-squared bishop so that in the event of ...dxc4, Bxc4 would win a tempo. Furthermore, White makes sure that a recapture with the bishop on c3 is always possible, so quite often a3 will be played, as ...Bxc3 has now somewhat lost its appeal. Additionally, White clears the c1-square for the rook. }
6... b6
{ I recommend setups starting with this move. After the trade on d5, we will often drop our dark-squared bishop back to either d6 or f8 @@StartBracket@@after ...Re8@@EndBracket@@. We will react depending on what White will do. If White puts the knight on e5, followed by f4, we will often undermine White's center with ...c5 and ...Nc6. }
7. cxd5
{ 7.Rc1  will likely transpose to  7.cxd5  exd5  8.Rc1  , as after @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/p1p2ppp/1p2pn2/3p4/1bPP4/2N1PN2/PP1B1PPP/2RQKB1R b K - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bb7  ,  White has nothing better than  8.cxd5  . }
7... exd5 8. Bd3 Bd6
{ It might look somewhat unnatural to move the same piece twice in the opening, but this move is the most accurate. We want to play ...Re8 quickly as well, to stop White from playing Ne5. }
9. Ne5
{ If White wants to get this move in, it should be done now, as otherwise, we will play ...Re8, preventing White from posting the knight in the center. }
9... c5 { Putting pressure on White's center right away. } 10. Rc1 Bb7
{ Preparing to put further pressure on d4 and e5 with ...Nc6. } 11. O-O Nc6 12.
Ng4 Ne8 13. f4
{ White cannot take on d5 since  13.Nxd5?  runs into  13...h5!  and the knight on g4 is trapped:  14.Nh6+  gxh6  15.Qxh5  Qg5-+  . }
13... f5 14. Ne5 cxd4 15. Nxc6 Bxc6 16. exd4 Qd7
{ Protecting the pawn on f5, so we can play ...Nf6 next, after which Black is already slightly for choice. }
