{ I recommend setups starting with this move. After the trade on d5, we will often drop our dark-squared bishop back to either d6 or f8 @@StartBracket@@after ...Re8@@EndBracket@@. We will react depending on what White will do. If White puts the knight on e5, followed by f4, we will often undermine White's center with ...c5 and ...Nc6. }
7. cxd5
{ 7.Rc1  will likely transpose to  7.cxd5  exd5  8.Rc1  , as after @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/p1p2ppp/1p2pn2/3p4/1bPP4/2N1PN2/PP1B1PPP/2RQKB1R b K - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bb7  ,  White has nothing better than  8.cxd5  . }
7... exd5 8. Bd3 Bd6
{ It might look somewhat unnatural to move the same piece twice in the opening, but this move is the most accurate. We want to play ...Re8 quickly as well, to stop White from playing Ne5. }
9. O-O Re8
{ By activating the rook, we stop White from playing Ne5. Furthermore, Nb5 can now comfortably be met by ...Bf8. }
10. Nb5
{ Pushing our d6-bishop back, so White’s knight can get access to the e5-square. }
10... Bf8
{ The best square for our bishop, as it keeps the rook on e8 active. Moreover, we do not want to let White trade our bishop for the knight, as White would get quite a stable advantage due to the bishop pair. }
11. Ne5 { The point behind White’s last move. } 11... Ba6
{ Activating our bishop. Next up, we want to push White’s b5-knight away with ...c6 so we can trade off White’s active bishop on d3, or play ...c5, which would threaten ...c4. }
12. Rc1 { Attacking c7. Our response is forced here. } 12... c5
{ The only way to properly address White's threat. } 13. a4 Bb7
{ All of this was played in Nakamura-Vidit, chess.com 2020. Black is already a bit better, as we will play ...Nc6 next, to put pressure on White's center, and we can always play ...a6 to kick White's knight on b5 away. }
