7. cxd5
{ 7.Rc1  will likely transpose to  7.cxd5  exd5  8.Rc1  , as after @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/p1p2ppp/1p2pn2/3p4/1bPP4/2N1PN2/PP1B1PPP/2RQKB1R b K - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bb7  ,  White has nothing better than  8.cxd5  . }
7... exd5 8. Bd3 Bd6
{ It might look somewhat unnatural to move the same piece twice in the opening, but this move is the most accurate. We want to play ...Re8 quickly as well, to stop White from playing Ne5. }
9. O-O Re8
{ By activating the rook, we stop White from playing Ne5. Furthermore, Nb5 can now comfortably be met by ...Bf8. }
10. Nb5
{ Pushing our d6-bishop back, so White’s knight can get access to the e5-square. }
10... Bf8
{ The best square for our bishop, as it keeps the rook on e8 active. Moreover, we do not want to let White trade our bishop for the knight, as White would get quite a stable advantage due to the bishop pair. }
11. Ne5 { The point behind White’s last move. } 11... Ba6
{ Activating our bishop. Next up, we want to push White’s b5-knight away with ...c6 so we can trade off White’s active bishop on d3, or play ...c5, which would threaten ...c4. }
12. Be1
{ This is Swiercz's suggested novelty in his 1.d4 course. There is some venom to White's game plan, but Black will get a good game with accurate moves and also, we could potentially get chances to play for more than equality. We just have to be aware of White's f4 and Bh4 plan, in order to meet that accordingly. }
12... c6
{ The best move, kicking White’s annoying knight from b5 and strengthening our center. }
13. Nc3 Bxd3 14. Qxd3 Qc8
{ The most accurate. By defending the pawn on c6 once more, we now enable ourselves to play ...Nbd7 quickly. }
15. Rc1 Nbd7 16. f4 Qb7
{ Getting out of the x-ray of the rook on c1, and clearing up the c8-square for one of our rooks. }
17. Bh4 b5
{ With this move, we prepare a potential ...b4, to kick White’s knight from c3 and get more control of the e4-square. }
18. Bxf6 Nxf6 19. Rc2
{ Swiercz evaluates this position as unclear, and I agree. Both sides have their play and Black is not worse. }
19... Nd7
{ We have the idea of a potential ...Nb6-c4. Furthermore, this also enables us to kick the knight away from e5 with ...f6. }
