{ 9.Nb5  is still a possibility, but it has lost its punch compared to the note on 8...Re8. The subtle difference could be illustrated best in the following line: }
9... Bxd2+ 10. Nxd2
{ White might be hoping that we will defend the pawn on c7 passively, but we have other intentions. }
10... c5
{ Surprisingly, this move has not been played before. By sacrificing a pawn, we open the position and take advantage of the fact that White is still two moves away from castling.   Black is for choice since, instead of  10...c5  ,  10...c6  or  10...a6  is also possible, with the idea that after  11.Nxc7  @@StartBracket@@  11.Nc3  is met by  11...c5  , when Black's pieces are optimally placed.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/1bN2ppp/pp3n2/3p4/3P4/4P3/PP1N1PPP/2RQKB1R b K - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Ra7  , White  has to work hard to rescue the opportunist on c7. }
11. dxc5
{ White should accept the sacrifice, as otherwise, we can get a nice clamp on the queenside with ...c4, ...a6, and ...b5. }
11... bxc5 12. Rxc5 Nc6
{ Black gets great compensation, as we can follow up here with moves such as ...d4 and ...Qe7. }
