{ More accurate than  8...Re8  . After  9.Nb5  Bxd2+  10.Nxd2  ,  we are forced to play  10...c6  11.Nc3  and White has a very small edge. }
9. Bd3 Re8 10. Ne5
{ 10.O-O  will likely transpose to the main line as after  10...Bf8  ,  White has nothing better than  11.Ne5  . }
10... Bf8
{ We want to drop the bishop back before playing ...c5 because if we leave the bishop on b4, White could force us to give it up with a3. }
11. O-O c5 { Exerting pressure on White’s center. } 12. f4
{ Strengthening the knight on e5. } 12... Nc6
{ Exerting more pressure on the d4-pawn. Now ...cxd4 is a threat that White has to address somehow. }
13. Bb5
{ White addresses the threat on the d4-pawn by pinning the knight on c6. However, we easily have this covered. }
13... Rc8 { Activating the rook and defending the knight on c6. } 14. Be1
{ The point behind this move is to play Bh4 and exert pressure on the f6-knight. Before White is able to do so, we will play: }
14... a6
{ Attacking the bishop on b5 in order to break the pin on our knight on c6. }
15. Bxc6
{ We do not have to be worried about  15.Nxc6  ,  as after  15...Bxc6  16.Bxa6  Ra8⩱  ,  Black will win the pawn back with a slightly better position. }
15... Bxc6
{ Next, we will drop the bishop back to b7, and we can always follow up with ...cxd4, ...b5, and ...Qb6. }
