{ This line has become quite critical in recent years. White's idea is to delay the development of the light-squared bishop so that in the event of ...dxc4, Bxc4 would win a tempo. Furthermore, White makes sure that a recapture with the bishop on c3 is always possible, so quite often a3 will be played, as ...Bxc3 has now somewhat lost its appeal. Additionally, White clears the c1-square for the rook. }
6... b6
{ I recommend setups starting with this move. After the trade on d5, we will often drop our dark-squared bishop back to either d6 or f8 @@StartBracket@@after ...Re8@@EndBracket@@. We will react depending on what White will do. If White puts the knight on e5, followed by f4, we will often undermine White's center with ...c5 and ...Nc6. }
7. cxd5
{ 7.Rc1  will likely transpose to  7.cxd5  exd5  8.Rc1  , as after @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/p1p2ppp/1p2pn2/3p4/1bPP4/2N1PN2/PP1B1PPP/2RQKB1R b K - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bb7  ,  White has nothing better than  8.cxd5  . }
7... exd5 8. Rc1 Bb7
{ More accurate than  8...Re8  . After  9.Nb5  Bxd2+  10.Nxd2  ,  we are forced to play  10...c6  11.Nc3  and White has a very small edge. }
9. Bd3 Re8 10. Ne5
{ 10.O-O  will likely transpose to the main line as after  10...Bf8  ,  White has nothing better than  11.Ne5  . }
10... Bf8
{ We want to drop the bishop back before playing ...c5 because if we leave the bishop on b4, White could force us to give it up with a3. }
11. O-O c5 { Exerting pressure on White’s center. } 12. f4
{ Strengthening the knight on e5. } 12... Nc6
{ Exerting more pressure on the d4-pawn. Now ...cxd4 is a threat that White has to address somehow. }
13. Nxd5
{ As flashy as this move looks, it leads to a forced draw... or a wild position after Black has sacrificed the queen! }
13... Qxd5
{ You should not touch the knight, of course, since after  13...Nxd5?  14.Bxh7+  Kxh7  15.Qh5+  Kg8  16.Qxf7+  , Black is doomed, as  16...Kh7  17.Rf3  leads to a mating attack. }
14. Bc4
{ I will leave the choice to you here.  14...Qd8  leads to a forced draw after  15.Nxf7  Qc7  16.Nh6+  @@StartBracket@@The materialistic  16.Nd6+  Kh8  17.Nxe8  Rxe8∓  brings White nothing but a serious crisis on the central pawns and light squares.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r3rbk1/pbq3pp/1pnN1n2/2p5/2BP1P2/4P3/PP1B2PP/2RQ1RK1 b - - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Kh8  17.Nf7+  , and @@StartFEN@@r3rbk1/pb3ppp/1pn2n2/2pqN3/2BP1P2/4P3/PP1B2PP/2RQ1RK1 b - - 1 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Qxg2+  @@StartBracket@@yes, you read that right@@EndBracket@@ leads to a fun game. }
14... Qxg2+ 15. Kxg2 Nxe5+ 16. Kg1 Nxc4 17. Rxc4 Rad8
{ Black only has a knight and bishop for the sacrificed queen, but Black's pieces coordinate beautifully and White's king is quite exposed.   We should not try to regain some of the material with  17...Ba6  , as the light-squared bishop is a crucial piece in our initiative against the white king.   We can follow up here with a quick ...Ne4, and potentially a rook lift to go after the king on g1. In practice, Black’s position is much easier to play, and White will need to be extremely careful here. }
