21. Qg8 Be7
{ We attack the queen once again and enable ourselves to meet Bf4+ with ...Bg5. }
22. Rxc8 { 22.Bf4+  Bg5  23.Rxc8  Bxc8  transposes to the main line. } 22...
Bxc8
{ We should recapture with the bishop so our queen can still recapture on g5. }
23. Bf4+ Bg5 24. Bxg5+ Qxg5
{ We have to sacrifice the rook on e8, but in return, we get plenty of counterplay. }
25. Qxe8 Qxe3+ 26. Kh1
{ White's only move.  26.Rf2??  would not be a good idea because of  26...Nd3-+  and White can resign. }
26... Qxe2
{ After a series of only moves, it is actually White who has to be careful here to maintain the balance. }
27. Rc1
{ White avoids an immediate draw with this move. However, it contains serious risk, as now we will get our chances to play for more. }
27... Nd3
{ The knight jumps in and Black is already creating serious threats. } 28. Rc6+
{ White's only move to not lose.  28.Qxc8?  was played in Sarana-Sevian, chess.com 2022, but this loses for a number of reasons. The most straightforward being  28...Ne1  29.Rc6+  Kh5  30.Qe8+  g6  31.g4+  Qxg4-+  . }
28... Kg5
{ This might look somewhat scary but Black's king is actually quite safe. } 29.
h3
{ White's best move. We can always make a draw by giving a perpetual check here, but we can also go for more after, for example,  29.Qe7+?  , which was played in Keymer-Bjerre, Terme Catez 2021, but Black won quickly following  29...Kf4  30.h3  Qe1+  31.Kh2  Qg3+-+  . }
29... Qf1+
{ We flick in the check first since the immediate  29...Bxf5  30.Qe7+  makes it harder for our king to run away  via f4.  Why that is, will soon become apparent. }
30. Kh2 Bxf5 31. Qe7+ Kf4
{ Black's king will sit quite safely on e3. Of course, the position is still a mess, but Black is already for choice. Note that  32.Qh4+  Ke3  33.Qg5+  can now be met with  33...Qf4+  , which is why we played our 29th move.  If Black would still  have the queen on e2 in this position, the bishop on f5 would simply fall. }
