7. cxd5
{ 7.Rc1  will likely transpose to  7.cxd5  exd5  8.Rc1  , as after @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/p1p2ppp/1p2pn2/3p4/1bPP4/2N1PN2/PP1B1PPP/2RQKB1R b K - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Bb7  ,  White has nothing better than  8.cxd5  . }
7... exd5 8. Rc1 Bb7
{ More accurate than  8...Re8  . After  9.Nb5  Bxd2+  10.Nxd2  ,  we are forced to play  10...c6  11.Nc3  and White has a very small edge. }
9. Bd3 Re8 10. Ne5
{ 10.O-O  will likely transpose to the main line as after  10...Bf8  ,  White has nothing better than  11.Ne5  . }
10... Bf8
{ We want to drop the bishop back before playing ...c5 because if we leave the bishop on b4, White could force us to give it up with a3. }
11. O-O c5 { Exerting pressure on White’s center. } 12. f4
{ Strengthening the knight on e5. } 12... Nc6
{ Exerting more pressure on the d4-pawn. Now ...cxd4 is a threat that White has to address somehow. }
13. Ne2 { Defending the pawn on d4. } 13... Rc8 14. Be1
{ The only critical move. White's idea is to play Bh4 and exert pressure on the f6-knight. }
14... Ne4
{ Moving the knight into the center before White can pin it. This move leads to massive complications, but Black is not on the worse side of them. As the lines get quite forced from here, I highly recommend you revise the moves diligently with the MoveTrainer®. }
15. Bxe4
{ If White does not go for the long forcing variation we are about to see here, Black will have a very comfortable position, as we can quickly play ...f6 to push back the knight from e5. }
15... dxe4 16. Nxf7
{ This knight sacrifice might come as a bolt from the blue, but with accurate defense, Black has nothing to worry about. }
16... Kxf7 { Of course, we should take the knight. } 17. Qb3+
{ The point behind the knight sacrifice. Since our king cannot go back, it will be dragged out into the open. But before we move our king, we should play ...c4. }
17... c4
{ It is crucial that we get this move in. As we will find out later, we will always have defensive resources related to White's queen on c4 that can come under attack. }
18. Qxc4+ Kg6
{ The only move. Moving the king to any other square would lead to colossal material losses. }
19. f5+ Kh6 { Again the only move. } 20. Bg3
{ White brings out the bishop to continue the attack with a quick Bf4. } 20...
Ne5
{ The point of @@StartFEN@@2rqrb2/pb3kpp/1pn5/2p5/3PpP2/1Q2P3/PP2N1PP/2R1BRK1 b - - 1 17@@EndFEN@@  17...c4  . The knight will be crucial in the defense of our king. }
21. Qg8 Be7
{ We attack the queen once again and enable ourselves to meet Bf4+ with ...Bg5. }
22. Rxc8 Bxc8
{ We should recapture with the bishop so our queen can still recapture on g5. }
23. Bf4+ Bg5 24. Bxg5+ Qxg5
{ We have to sacrifice the rook on e8, but in return, we get plenty of counterplay. }
25. Qxe8 Qxe3+ 26. Kh1
{ White's only move.  26.Rf2??  would not be a good idea because of  26...Nd3-+  and White can resign. }
26... Qxe2
{ After a series of only moves, it is actually White who has to be careful here to maintain the balance. }
27. Ra1 { White's best move. } 27... Qxb2 28. Rf1
{ Again, the only move for White to maintain the balance. } 28... Qe2 29. Ra1
Qb2 { Black also has alternatives, but ultimately they all lead to draws. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Rubinstein System 4.e3 O-O 5.Bd3 − Main Line"]
[Black "Rubinstein System 5.Bd3 d5 6.Nf3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3
{ The Rubinstein System against the Nimzo − White can adopt a lot of setups after this move, such as @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQ - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bd3  and 6.Nf3,  5.Bd3  and 6.Nge2,  5.Bd2  , and  5.Nge2  right away. We will have to respond differently to all of White's setups, but in all cases, Black gets a good game and also has a fair share of chances to take over the initiative. }
4... O-O 5. Bd3
{ White’s most popular continuation, which keeps all the options open. White can develop the g1-knight to e2 or f3, and we will respond to both moves in a similar fashion: by playing ...d5xc4 and ...c5xd4 to give White an isolated pawn on d4. White can also opt for a quick a3 to make us trade on c3, so they get the bishop pair and more pawns in the center. }
5... d5
{ Our best continuation. Often, we will aim for ...dxc4 followed by ...c5xd4, to give White an isolated pawn on d4. }
6. Nf3
{ Traditionally, this has been the main line of the 4.e3 Nimzo. However, these days Black is doing quite well against this line, as we have an effective antidote. }
6... dxc4 7. Bxc4 c5
{ The point of the ...dxc4 and ...cxd4 trades is to give White an isolated pawn on d4. }
8. O-O cxd4 9. Nxd4
{ Taking with the knight is quite toothless, as White's bishop on c1 remains passive. }
9... Bd7
{ We will follow with ...Nc6 and Black has absolutely nothing to worry about. }
*

