[White "3) Rubinstein System 4.e3 O-O 5.Bd3 − Main Line"]
[Black "Rubinstein System 5.Bd3 d5 6.Nf3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3
{ The Rubinstein System against the Nimzo − White can adopt a lot of setups after this move, such as @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQ - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bd3  and 6.Nf3,  5.Bd3  and 6.Nge2,  5.Bd2  , and  5.Nge2  right away. We will have to respond differently to all of White's setups, but in all cases, Black gets a good game and also has a fair share of chances to take over the initiative. }
4... O-O 5. Bd3
{ White’s most popular continuation, which keeps all the options open. White can develop the g1-knight to e2 or f3, and we will respond to both moves in a similar fashion: by playing ...d5xc4 and ...c5xd4 to give White an isolated pawn on d4. White can also opt for a quick a3 to make us trade on c3, so they get the bishop pair and more pawns in the center. }
5... d5
{ Our best continuation. Often, we will aim for ...dxc4 followed by ...c5xd4, to give White an isolated pawn on d4. }
6. Nf3
{ Traditionally, this has been the main line of the 4.e3 Nimzo. However, these days Black is doing quite well against this line, as we have an effective antidote. }
6... dxc4 7. Bxc4 c5
{ The point of the ...dxc4 and ...cxd4 trades is to give White an isolated pawn on d4. }
8. O-O cxd4 9. exd4
{ This is White's only move to keep any hopes of an opening advantage alive. We will have the better pawn structure, but White has a slight lead in development. If we are able to get fully developed, we will have a comfortable position. However, before we are able to do so, White can try to pose some problems. }
9... b6
{ We want to fianchetto the light-squared bishop on b7 to make it difficult for White to get the d5 break in. Next, we will develop our knight to d7 or c6, depending on the circumstances.  A lot of games have been played in this position, but Black has absolutely nothing to worry about and we will also get our chance to take over the initiative. }
10. Qe2 Bb7 11. Rd1
{ This move improves the placement of the white rook and enables White to meet both  11...Nbd7  and  11...Nc6  with  12.d5  .   11.Bg5  transposes to the 10.Bg5 move order. }
11... h6
{ Stopping 12.Bg5. I recommend avoiding the variations starting with  11...Nbd7  12.d5  ,  as they are quite forcing and tend to lead to slightly better and risk-free positions for White. }
12. a3 Bxc3
{ As we will often see, it is best just to trade on c3 since White's hanging pawns will be a clear target for counterplay. Furthermore, by trading off the knight on c3, we make sure that White can no longer get the d5 break in. }
13. bxc3 Qc7
{ The most accurate, as we discourage White from moving the bishop from c4 because that would hang the c3-pawn. Black has a fine position due to our better pawn structure, and we are going to follow up here with ...Nbd7 and ...Rac8. }
