[White "3) Rubinstein System 4.e3 O-O 5.Bd3 − Main Line"]
[Black "Rubinstein System 5.Bd3 d5 6.Nge2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3
{ The Rubinstein System against the Nimzo − White can adopt a lot of setups after this move, such as @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQ - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bd3  and 6.Nf3,  5.Bd3  and 6.Nge2,  5.Bd2  , and  5.Nge2  right away. We will have to respond differently to all of White's setups, but in all cases, Black gets a good game and also has a fair share of chances to take over the initiative. }
4... O-O 5. Bd3
{ White’s most popular continuation, which keeps all the options open. White can develop the g1-knight to e2 or f3, and we will respond to both moves in a similar fashion: by playing ...d5xc4 and ...c5xd4 to give White an isolated pawn on d4. White can also opt for a quick a3 to make us trade on c3, so they get the bishop pair and more pawns in the center. }
5... d5
{ Our best continuation. Often, we will aim for ...dxc4 followed by ...c5xd4, to give White an isolated pawn on d4. }
6. Ne2
{ A bit of a sideline. The arising positions will be similar to those in the  6.Nf3  variation.  However, the difference is that White’s knight is slightly misplaced on e2, as it is just more active on f3. }
6... dxc4
{ It is important to play this move first, as it limits White’s options. } 7.
Bxc4 c5
{ The standard continuation. We plan on taking on d4, to give White an isolated pawn on d4. }
8. O-O cxd4 9. exd4 Nc6
{ We have the better pawn structure and absolutely nothing to worry about in this position. Black is already slightly for choice, as it is often easier to play against the isolated pawn than with the isolated pawn. Testament to this evaluation is the fact that Wesley So outplayed with Black the Greek GM Mastrovasilis in the 2022 Chennai Olympiad.   We have a better version of the Karpov Nimzo here, as White's knight is worse on e2 than it would have been on f3. Against most of White's moves, we are going to play ...h6 to stop White from playing Bg5, while ...b6 followed by ...Bb7 will also often be a useful plan. }
10. Bg5
{ White can decide to pin our knight on f6 right away before we stop them from doing so with ...h6. However, we have an effective way to neutralize the pin. }
10... h6 11. Bh4 Be7
{ Effectively neutralizing the pin on the h4-d8 diagonal. Black is already slightly for choice due to our better pawn structure. Next, ...Qb6 followed by ...Rd8 and ...Bd7-e8 will often be an effective way to improve our position. }
