5... d5
{ Our best continuation. Often, we will aim for ...dxc4 followed by ...c5xd4, to give White an isolated pawn on d4. }
6. cxd5
{ This line has gained a lot in popularity over the last year. At first sight, it looks quite innocuous as the cxd5 and ...exd5 trade is generally in Black's favor. However, the position is somewhat easier to play for White and it is important that we know the right plan here. }
6... exd5 7. a3 Bd6 8. Nge2
{ Significantly less popular than  8.Qc2  − the difference is that White is not  threatening Nb5 now to get the bishop pair, which gives us the option to delay ...c6. }
8... Re8
{ We will continue in similar fashion. Our rook will always be well placed on the e-file and we keep our options open for our other pieces. }
9. O-O
{ If White plays  9.Qc2  ,  we can just play  9...c6  and transpose to the 8.Qc2 move order. }
9... Nbd7
{ By delaying ...c6, we keep the option of going ...c5 in one go. Black has a fine position here. Our plan will often be to follow up with ...b6 and ...c5, but going ...c5 right away is also not out of the question. }
