[White "3) Rubinstein System 4.e3 O-O 5.Bd3 − Main Line"]
[Black "Rubinstein System 5.Bd3 d5 6.cxd5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3
{ The Rubinstein System against the Nimzo − White can adopt a lot of setups after this move, such as @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQ - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bd3  and 6.Nf3,  5.Bd3  and 6.Nge2,  5.Bd2  , and  5.Nge2  right away. We will have to respond differently to all of White's setups, but in all cases, Black gets a good game and also has a fair share of chances to take over the initiative. }
4... O-O 5. Bd3
{ White’s most popular continuation, which keeps all the options open. White can develop the g1-knight to e2 or f3, and we will respond to both moves in a similar fashion: by playing ...d5xc4 and ...c5xd4 to give White an isolated pawn on d4. White can also opt for a quick a3 to make us trade on c3, so they get the bishop pair and more pawns in the center. }
5... d5
{ Our best continuation. Often, we will aim for ...dxc4 followed by ...c5xd4, to give White an isolated pawn on d4. }
6. cxd5
{ This line has gained a lot in popularity over the last year. At first sight, it looks quite innocuous as the cxd5 and ...exd5 trade is generally in Black's favor. However, the position is somewhat easier to play for White and it is important that we know the right plan here. }
6... exd5 7. Ne2 Re8 8. O-O Bd6 9. f3
{ With this move, White aims to build up a center with e3-e4. } 9... c5
{ Generally, this is how we should respond to f3 in the Carlsbad structure. The dxc5 and ...Bxc5 trade has now become much more appealing for us, as White's e3-pawn will be quite weak. }
10. Qe1
{ This is White's most popular move in this position. White aims to move the queen to h4 or f2 and eventually start an initiative on the kingside with a potential g4-g5. However, we should not be worried about this, as we have an effective antidote.   10.Kh1  is White's best move in this position, but it is not something we should be worried about.  10...Nc6=  ,  developing the knight and exerting more pressure on White's center. Black has a comfortable game here and we can continue improving our position with ...h6, ...b6, and ...Bb7. }
10... b6
{ The easiest way to take the sting out of White's play. We are aiming to play ...Ba6 quickly, to trade off White's light-squared bishop on d3.  Black is already for choice, as White's play on the kingside is not going anywhere without the light-squared bishop. After the trade on a6, we will continue improving our position with moves such as ...Qd7, ...Nc7, and ...Rad8. }
