{ The Rubinstein System against the Nimzo − White can adopt a lot of setups after this move, such as @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQ - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bd3  and 6.Nf3,  5.Bd3  and 6.Nge2,  5.Bd2  , and  5.Nge2  right away. We will have to respond differently to all of White's setups, but in all cases, Black gets a good game and also has a fair share of chances to take over the initiative. }
4... O-O 5. Bd3
{ White’s most popular continuation, which keeps all the options open. White can develop the g1-knight to e2 or f3, and we will respond to both moves in a similar fashion: by playing ...d5xc4 and ...c5xd4 to give White an isolated pawn on d4. White can also opt for a quick a3 to make us trade on c3, so they get the bishop pair and more pawns in the center. }
5... d5
{ Our best continuation. Often, we will aim for ...dxc4 followed by ...c5xd4, to give White an isolated pawn on d4. }
6. cxd5
{ This line has gained a lot in popularity over the last year. At first sight, it looks quite innocuous as the cxd5 and ...exd5 trade is generally in Black's favor. However, the position is somewhat easier to play for White and it is important that we know the right plan here. }
6... exd5 7. Ne2 Re8
{ The most accurate. We activate our rook on the e-file and keep our options open as to how we want to proceed. }
8. O-O Bd6
{ Again the most accurate move, as it keeps our position flexible. Often, ...b6 followed by ...c5 will be an effective plan. Furthermore, in case White plays Nf4, we will be able to trade our bishop for the knight and damage White’s pawn structure somewhat. }
9. Bd2 b6 { Preparing the ...c5 push to get more control in the center. } 10.
Nf4
{ The critical continuation. White attacks the pawn on d5 and therefore temporarily halts us from playing ...c5. For instance, after  10.Rc1  c5  , Black has a fine game, and we will have our chances to take over the initiative. }
10... Bxf4
{ Of course, it is a pity to part ways with the bishop pair, but with this trade, we double White's pawns. Also, we don't have to waste any time and we can play ...c5 quickly. }
11. exf4 c5 12. Be3 c4 13. Bc2 Nc6
{ We have a fine game here due to our better pawn structure. Furthermore, White's bishop pair is also not too scary, as White's doubled f-pawns block in the bishops somewhat. }
