1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3
{ The Rubinstein System against the Nimzo − White can adopt a lot of setups after this move, such as @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQ - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bd3  and 6.Nf3,  5.Bd3  and 6.Nge2,  5.Bd2  , and  5.Nge2  right away. We will have to respond differently to all of White's setups, but in all cases, Black gets a good game and also has a fair share of chances to take over the initiative. }
4... O-O 5. Bd3
{ White’s most popular continuation, which keeps all the options open. White can develop the g1-knight to e2 or f3, and we will respond to both moves in a similar fashion: by playing ...d5xc4 and ...c5xd4 to give White an isolated pawn on d4. White can also opt for a quick a3 to make us trade on c3, so they get the bishop pair and more pawns in the center. }
5... d5
{ Our best continuation. Often, we will aim for ...dxc4 followed by ...c5xd4, to give White an isolated pawn on d4. }
6. a3
{ This line has gained a lot in popularity recently. It leads to an interesting strategic imbalance as White will obtain the bishop pair and more pawns in the center, whereas Black has slightly more active piece play. It is imperative that we do not let White advance the pawns easily, as doing so could lead to a dangerous attack. }
6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 dxc4 8. Bxc4 c5 9. Bd3 Qc7
{ Threatening @@StartFEN@@rnb2rk1/ppq2ppp/4pn2/2p5/3P4/P1PBP3/5PPP/R1BQK1NR b KQ - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...cxd4  11.cxd4  Qc3+  forking the king and the rook, so White has to protect  the c3-square somehow. }
10. Bb2
{ 10.Ne2  transposes to the @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp3ppp/4pn2/2p5/2BP4/P1P1P3/5PPP/R1BQK1NR w KQ c6 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Ne2  Qc7  10.Bd3  variation. }
10... Nc6 { Preparing the typical ...e5 push in the center. } 11. f4
{ Preventing Black's ...e5 push. However, this weakens the light squares too much. }
11... b5
{ We grab space on the queenside and make use of the fact that the pawn is immune to capture. After all,  12.Bxb5  runs into  12...Rb8  13.Qe2  cxd4  , when White is  unable to recapture on d4.  That is because  14.exd4  Nxd4!  15.cxd4  Qa5+  regains the piece with large positional dividends. }
12. Nf3 Bb7 13. O-O
{ Again, the pawn on b5 should be left untouched by White. Following  13.Bxb5  cxd4  , White has no good way of recapturing the pawn.  Either a check on a5 will follow or,  after  14.exd4  , Black can already take on f4, or play the much stronger  14...Rab8  , which the engine believes already deserves at evaluation of -3! }
13... Na5
{ White's center and bishop pair are immobilized and Black gets good control of the light squares.   This time, if White plays  14.Bxb5  , our compensation will be purely positional in nature. Black starts with  14...c4  , making sure the bishop is out of play  on b5. Now, for instance,  15.Ba4  Rab8  16.Bc1  @@StartBracket@@...Bxf3 was a threat, winning a piece@@EndBracket@@  16...Nb3  gives Black total dominance on the light squares. We are a pawn down, yet the engine gives us a two-pawn advantage! }
