1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3
{ The Rubinstein System against the Nimzo − White can adopt a lot of setups after this move, such as @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQ - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bd3  and 6.Nf3,  5.Bd3  and 6.Nge2,  5.Bd2  , and  5.Nge2  right away. We will have to respond differently to all of White's setups, but in all cases, Black gets a good game and also has a fair share of chances to take over the initiative. }
4... O-O 5. Bd3
{ White’s most popular continuation, which keeps all the options open. White can develop the g1-knight to e2 or f3, and we will respond to both moves in a similar fashion: by playing ...d5xc4 and ...c5xd4 to give White an isolated pawn on d4. White can also opt for a quick a3 to make us trade on c3, so they get the bishop pair and more pawns in the center. }
5... d5
{ Our best continuation. Often, we will aim for ...dxc4 followed by ...c5xd4, to give White an isolated pawn on d4. }
6. a3
{ This line has gained a lot in popularity recently. It leads to an interesting strategic imbalance as White will obtain the bishop pair and more pawns in the center, whereas Black has slightly more active piece play. It is imperative that we do not let White advance the pawns easily, as doing so could lead to a dangerous attack. }
6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 dxc4 8. Bxc4 c5 9. Ne2 Qc7
{ Threatening ...cxd4, which would attack the bishop on c4, so White has to move the bishop. }
10. Ba2
{ The point behind dropping the bishop back to a2 is that here it will be more difficult for us to play ...e5. Instead of that, we are going to place our bishop on the a6-f1 diagonal, which White now has left unopposed. }
10... b6 11. O-O Ba6 12. Bb2
{ 12.Bb2 was played twice by Carlsen and we should therefore take this move seriously. }
12... Rd8
{ The d4-pawn is currently well defended, but White will eventually want to play e3-e4 or c3-c4, after which this move will prove to be useful, as we will have more pressure on the d4-pawn. }
13. Rc1 { White's best move, further preparing c4. } 13... Nc6 14. c4
{ Opening up the dark-squared bishop on b2, and preparing to gain even more space in the center with d5. We should act quickly, to neutralize White's play in the center. }
14... cxd4 15. exd4
{ White has the hanging pawns but is aiming to play d5 quickly, which could yield a dangerous initiative, as White's dark-squared bishop could become quite powerful. Fortunately, we have an effective antidote. }
15... b5 { Undermining the c4-pawn, so the d5 push loses in strength. } 16. d5
{ 16.cxb5  is quite toothless as after  16...Bxb5=  ,  White will not be able to get the d5 break in. }
16... bxc4 17. Bxf6 Rxd5
{ It is important to play this zwischenzug first before recapturing on f6. After  17...gxf6?  18.Bxc4  Bxc4  19.Rxc4  Rxd5  20.Qc1+-  ,  the pin on our knight and White's play against our king is just too much to handle. }
18. Qe1
{ If White plays  18.Qa4  ,  we should throw in one more zwischenzug with  18...Ra5  ,  forcing the queen to go back,  19.Qd1  gxf6  .  Finally, we take the bishop.  20.Bxc4  Rd8⩱  and White just does not have sufficient compensation for the sacrificed pawn.   The attempt to save the piece with  18.Bd4  runs into  18...Nxd4  , which is the most accurate reply. @@StartBracket@@For instance, the lazy  18...Rad8?  allows White to get back in the game with  19.Bxc4  Bxc4  20.Rxc4  Qd7  21.Rxc6  Qxc6  22.Qb3  , saving the day due to the back-rank mate. Since we cannot take on d4, we can't claim any advantage either.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r5k1/p1q2ppp/b3p3/3r4/2pn4/P7/B3NPPP/2RQ1RK1 w - - 0 19@@EndFEN@@  19.Nxd4  Qb6  @@StartBracket@@Again,  19...Rad8?  is a blunder, this time because of  20.Qa4  , when White escapes the pin since our bishop on a6 is under attack as well.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r5k1/p4ppp/bq2p3/3r4/2pN4/P7/B4PPP/2RQ1RK1 w - - 0 20@@EndFEN@@  20.Bxc4  Rxd4  21.Qf3  Bb7  and with a clean pawn up, we can be more than content. }
18... gxf6 { Of course, we should recapture the bishop. } 19. Bxc4 Bxc4 20.
Rxc4 Qb6
{ We are up a pawn here and White's threats are not too scary. Black is somewhat for choice, as the onus will be on White to prove the compensation. }
