[White "3) Rubinstein System 4.e3 O-O 5.Bd3 − Main Line"]
[Black "Rubinstein System 5.Bd3 d5 6.a3 #12"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3
{ The Rubinstein System against the Nimzo − White can adopt a lot of setups after this move, such as @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR w KQ - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bd3  and 6.Nf3,  5.Bd3  and 6.Nge2,  5.Bd2  , and  5.Nge2  right away. We will have to respond differently to all of White's setups, but in all cases, Black gets a good game and also has a fair share of chances to take over the initiative. }
4... O-O 5. Bd3
{ White’s most popular continuation, which keeps all the options open. White can develop the g1-knight to e2 or f3, and we will respond to both moves in a similar fashion: by playing ...d5xc4 and ...c5xd4 to give White an isolated pawn on d4. White can also opt for a quick a3 to make us trade on c3, so they get the bishop pair and more pawns in the center. }
5... d5
{ Our best continuation. Often, we will aim for ...dxc4 followed by ...c5xd4, to give White an isolated pawn on d4. }
6. a3
{ This line has gained a lot in popularity recently. It leads to an interesting strategic imbalance as White will obtain the bishop pair and more pawns in the center, whereas Black has slightly more active piece play. It is imperative that we do not let White advance the pawns easily, as doing so could lead to a dangerous attack. }
6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 dxc4 8. Bxc4 c5 9. Ne2 Qc7
{ Threatening ...cxd4, which would attack the bishop on c4, so White has to move the bishop. }
10. Bd3 Nc6
{ Preparing ...e5. It is important that we always play ...Nc6 before playing ...e5, as otherwise White can take on e5 and force us to recapture with our queen. }
11. O-O e5 12. Ng3
{ I found 19@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ games by the strong Russian GM Alexey Sarana in the database from this position. White's idea often is to sacrifice the pawn on d4 in order to create a strong attack with his bishops. He has won many great games in rapid and blitz, but the opening experts have found a way to neutralize White's play.   After both  12.Qc2  Be6  and @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/ppq2ppp/2n2n2/2p1p3/3P4/P1PBP3/4NPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Bb2  Be6  followed by ...Rad8, Black's position is preferable. }
12... Be6 13. f4 exd4 14. cxd4 Rad8
{ It is important to not take twice, and just activate our rook on the d-file. A game of cat and mouse begins here, in which White does not want to take on c5, and neither do we want to take on d4, as White will always play e4 and start rolling the pawns.   Instead of taking on d4, we are going to expand on the queenside with ...a6 and ...b5 since  14...cxd4  15.e4  is a line we should avoid. White just starts rolling the pawns forward on the kingside and the attack is difficult to stop. }
15. Rb1 a6 16. h3 b5 17. Bb2 Nd5
{ There are other options as well, but this is the most straightforward. } 18.
dxc5 Nxe3
{ Forking the queen and the rook. White has nothing better here than to go for a perpetual check. }
19. Bxh7+ Kxh7 20. Qh5+ Kg8 21. Bxg7 Kxg7 22. Qg5+ Kh7
{ After  23.Qh4+  Kg8  24.Qg5+  Kh7  , a draw is imminent.  It would be risky to play for more here, but White can still try to avoid the repetition with Rf3. }
23. Rf3 { We should not be worried about this, as we have a good antidote. }
23... Qe7 24. Qh5+ Kg7 25. f5
{ Attacking the bishop and threatening f6+. This is also White's only move, as otherwise, ...Rh8 would just push the queen back and there would be no attack at all. }
25... Rh8
{ Our only move to keep the advantage and not get worse. White's queen is trapped so the following sequence is forced. }
26. f6+ { Forking the king and queen. } 26... Qxf6 27. Rxf6 Rxh5 28. Nxh5+ Kg8
{ After the dust has settled, we land in this endgame, where Black is clearly the one playing for the win, as our minor pieces are better than White's rook. }
