{ This is the only move White can try to not transpose.   In case of  12.Bb2  ,  we can just transpose to the main line after  12...Bxe2  13.Qxe2  cxd4  14.cxd4  Nbd7  . }
12... Nxa6 13. Bb2 cxd4
{ Opening up the c-file is a good idea here, as we are more likely to take advantage of it. Furthermore, after cxd4 we will get a 2 vs. 1 majority on the queenside, which we can potentially use to create a passed pawn. }
14. exd4
{ White can also recapture this way, but we should not be worried about it, as this gives White hanging pawns. }
14... Nb8
{ Our knight is headed to c6, from where it will exert pressure on the d4-pawn and potentially continue its route to a5, from where it will exert pressure on the c4-pawn @@StartBracket@@White will probably play c4 in the next couple of moves@@EndBracket@@. }
15. a4 Rd8
{ Against the hanging pawns, we generally want to place our rooks on d8 and c8, to exert maximum pressure on the d- and c-pawns. }
16. Rc1 { White prepares the c4 push. } 16... Nc6
{ Bringing our knight into the game. } 17. c4
{ This makes the pawns slightly more vulnerable, but White really should not wait with this move, as otherwise, we could try to establish a blockade on the c4-square with ...Rac8 and ...Na5, and White's bishop on b2 would be terribly passive. }
17... Rac8
{ Black has a fine game here, as we have the slightly better pawn structure. We can play ...Na5 in the foreseeable future, to exert more pressure on the c4-pawn. }
