[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Classical Variation 4.Qc2 d5 5.a3 & Others"]
[Black "Classical Variation 4.Qc2 d5 5.Nf3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2
{ The Classical Variation of the Nimzo. The idea behind this move is twofold: White enables the recapture on c3 with the queen and can therefore keep the structure intact. Furthermore, with this move, White also enables the move e4. }
4... d5
{ I recommend this move, as I would like to avoid the lines starting with  4...O-O  5.e4  . This gives White the additional option of @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/1bPP4/2N5/PPQ1PPPP/R1B1KBNR w KQkq d6 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.cxd5  , but those lines actually work out quite nicely for Black, as I will offer you a combative antidote. }
5. Nf3 { This move will likely transpose to one of the other lines. } 5... O-O
{ Castling is the best move, as it keeps our options open. } 6. Bg5
{ After  6.e3  c5  , we transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/1bPP4/2N5/PPQ1PPPP/R1B1KBNR w KQkq d6 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.e3  O-O  6.Nf3  .   In case of  6.a3  Bxc3+  7.Qxc3  b6  , we transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/1bPP4/2N5/PPQ1PPPP/R1B1KBNR w KQkq d6 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.a3  Bxc3+  6.Qxc3  O-O  7.Nf3  .   And if  6.cxd5  exd5  7.Bg5  c5  , we transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/1bPP4/2N5/PPQ1PPPP/R1B1KBNR w KQkq d6 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.cxd5  exd5  6.Nf3  c5  7.Bg5  O-O  . }
6... h6 { Forcing White to make a decision with the dark-squared bishop. } 7.
Bh4
{ This is the only reasonable line that I could find that does not transpose into one of the other variations that are covered. It is actually important to know how to proceed.   7.Bxf6  will likely transpose to another main line since after  7...Qxf6  ,  White's best move is  8.a3  Bxc3+  9.Qxc3  , which transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/1bPP4/2N5/PPQ1PPPP/R1B1KBNR w KQkq d6 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.a3  Bxc3+  6.Qxc3  O-O  7.Bg5  . }
7... c5
{ I recommend this move, as we respond similarly to other variations and we could still transpose to some of the other lines.   7...dxc4  is possible as well, but things get extremely complicated after  8.e4  g5  9.Bg3  b5  10.e5  ,  and Wesley So scored a crushing victory here over Levon Aronian, chess24.com 2021. }
8. e3
{ After  8.cxd5  exd5  , we will also transpose to the variations starting with @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/1bPP4/2N5/PPQ1PPPP/R1B1KBNR w KQkq d6 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.cxd5  exd5  6.Nf3  c5  7.Bg5  O-O  . }
8... cxd4 9. Nxd4
{ In case of  9.exd4  Nc6  ,  Black will also get an excellent game, as White will soon get an isolated pawn on d4. }
9... e5
{ Pushing White's knight away and grabbing space in the center. Black has an excellent game here, as we have plenty of activity. }
