[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Classical Variation 4.Qc2 d5 5.a3 & Others"]
[Black "Classical Variation 4.Qc2 d5 5.a3 − 7.e3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2
{ The Classical Variation of the Nimzo. The idea behind this move is twofold: White enables the recapture on c3 with the queen and can therefore keep the structure intact. Furthermore, with this move, White also enables the move e4. }
4... d5
{ I recommend this move, as I would like to avoid the lines starting with  4...O-O  5.e4  . This gives White the additional option of @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/1bPP4/2N5/PPQ1PPPP/R1B1KBNR w KQkq d6 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.cxd5  , but those lines actually work out quite nicely for Black, as I will offer you a combative antidote. }
5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 O-O
{ White has a lot of positional trumps: the bishop pair, and the one bishop we have is somewhat blocked in by our pawns. However, the drawback of White's play is that our opponent is quite far behind in development and it will take quite a long time before White will get castled. Because of this, it is of utmost importance that we open up the center quickly and try to strike before White can get fully developed. }
7. e3
{ Nakamura has played this quite a few times. White's idea is to be able to recapture on c4 with the bishop. However, the drawback is that the dark-squared bishop becomes a bit passive now. }
7... b6
{ We stick to the same plan and activate our bishop on either b7 or a6. } 8.
cxd5
{ The point of this move order.  8.Nf3  would transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/P1Q5/1P2PPPP/R1B1KBNR w KQ - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nf3  b6  8.e3  . }
8... Nxd5
{ The right recapture. By attacking the queen on c3, we buy ourselves time to develop a nice initiative. }
9. Qc2 Bb7 10. e4 { This has been played twice in blitz games by Nakamura. }
10... Nf6
{ We provoke the pawn to come forward to e5, which leads to a double-edged position. On one hand, White can use the space advantage on the kingside to try to launch an attack. On the other hand, White will be left with some weaknesses after having played e5 that we can try to exploit. }
11. e5 Nd5 12. Nf3 Ne7
{ Next up, we can either play ...Nd7 and ...c5, or exert a lot of pressure on the pawn by going ...Nbc6, followed by ...Nf5. Note that  13.Ng5  can now be comfortably met with  13...Nf5  . }
