[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Classical Variation 4.Qc2 d5 5.a3 & Others"]
[Black "Classical Variation 4.Qc2 d5 5.a3 − 7.Nf3 #14"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2
{ The Classical Variation of the Nimzo. The idea behind this move is twofold: White enables the recapture on c3 with the queen and can therefore keep the structure intact. Furthermore, with this move, White also enables the move e4. }
4... d5
{ I recommend this move, as I would like to avoid the lines starting with  4...O-O  5.e4  . This gives White the additional option of @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/1bPP4/2N5/PPQ1PPPP/R1B1KBNR w KQkq d6 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.cxd5  , but those lines actually work out quite nicely for Black, as I will offer you a combative antidote. }
5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 O-O
{ White has a lot of positional trumps: the bishop pair, and the one bishop we have is somewhat blocked in by our pawns. However, the drawback of White's play is that our opponent is quite far behind in development and it will take quite a long time before White will get castled. Because of this, it is of utmost importance that we open up the center quickly and try to strike before White can get fully developed. }
7. Nf3
{ This is the traditional main line of the 4.Qc2 Nimzo, but in recent years it has lost its punch somewhat. White's hope for an edge is based on having the bishop pair, and in the event of ...dxc4, White will also get a slightly better pawn structure. In return, we have a lead in development, as White is quite far from getting the kingside developed and getting castled. }
7... b6
{ Black's most common response to 7.Nf3 is  7...dxc4  8.Qxc4  b6  . However, I recommend playing @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/P1Q2N2/1P2PPPP/R1B1KB1R b KQ - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...b6  first as we avoid the h4 line:  7...dxc4  8.Qxc4  b6  9.h4  . }
8. Bg5 dxc4 9. Qxc4 Ba6 10. Qa4 h6
{ The inclusion of ...h6 Bh4 is almost always useful for us. } 11. Bh4 c5
{ This direct approach has become an effective antidote against this line. Our pawn structure gets weakened, as we will get some isolated and doubled pawns, but we will get quick development since after the dxc5 and ...bxc5 trade, our queen gets access to the b6-square after which our knight can also comfortably develop to c6. Furthermore, our rooks can utilize the open d- and b-files to generate counterplay. }
12. dxc5 bxc5 13. Rc1 Qb6
{ Defending the pawn on c5 and attacking the pawn on b2. } 14. Bxf6
{ White's only move to maintain the balance. } 14... gxf6 15. Rc2 c4
{ Depriving White of giving an annoying check on g4. Furthermore, we can now gain a lot of tempi against the white queen. }
16. e3 Bb5 17. Qb4 { White's only move. } 17... Rc8
{ Activating the rook and defending the pawn on c4. } 18. Be2
{ 18.Qc3  Nd7  19.Be2  Ba4  followed by  ...Nc5 in case of  19.Rd2  , or  ...Rab8 if White plays  19.Rc1  instead. Black is better in both cases. }
18... Na6 19. Qc3
{ If White plays  19.Qd2  ,  we will proceed in the same manner  19...Ba4  20.Rc3   Taking the pawn with  20.Rxc4  is not a good idea, as Black gets a strong initiative after  20...Rxc4  21.Bxc4  Rd8↑  .  20...Rab8=  Black has a fine game here, as we will probably end up giving up our pawn on c4 in return for the pawn on b2 and we have plenty of activity. }
19... Ba4
{ Attacking the rook on c2 and forcing White to move it to either d2 or c1. Both moves have their drawbacks and we should respond to both moves differently. }
20. Rd2 Nc5 21. Qxc4
{ After  21.Qxf6?  Ne4-+  , Black simply wins material and White's attack is not breaking through. }
21... Nb3 22. Qg4+ Kh8 23. Rd1
{ With this move, White declines the trade of two minor pieces for the rook and makes sure that we do not have the dangerous ...Rc1+. However, we have other ways to continue our initiative. }
23... Qa5+
{ Just before White is able to castle, we can throw in this annoying check. }
24. Qb4 { White's only move not to lose right away. } 24... Rab8
{ We have to allow a queen trade, but our initiative continues in the endgame. }
25. Qxa5 Nxa5
{ White will have to return the pawn on b2 and we will keep a great initiative in the endgame. }
