7. Bg5 h6
{ After careful consideration, I have chosen to recommend this move.   7...dxc4  and  7...c5  are also possible but lead to extremely sharp variations where Black could be in big trouble if a line is forgotten or if Black is surprised by a dangerous novelty. The text, however, is rock-solid and provides a comfortable path to equality. }
8. Bh4 c5
{ The inclusion of @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p2B1/2PP4/P1Q5/1P2PPPP/R3KBNR b KQ - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7...h6  8.Bh4  makes this a much better version of the pawn sacrifice. }
9. cxd5 g5 { Breaking the pin. } 10. Bg3 Ne4
{ After White moves the queen, we will play ...Qa5+, to which White does not have a proper response. Black will get a crushing attack. For example  11.Qc2  Qa5+  12.Kd1  Bd7-+  . }
