{ After careful consideration, I have chosen to recommend this move.   7...dxc4  and  7...c5  are also possible but lead to extremely sharp variations where Black could be in big trouble if a line is forgotten or if Black is surprised by a dangerous novelty. The text, however, is rock-solid and provides a comfortable path to equality. }
8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. Nf3 dxc4 10. Qxc4 Nc6
{ The point behind this move is to play ...e5 quickly. } 11. Qc3
{ Stopping the ...e5 push from Black. } 11... Re8
{ Reinforcing the ...e5 push. White cannot stop us from playing ...e5 here but can try to anticipate it. }
12. Rd1
{ The only critical move, making sure that after  12...e5  13.d5  , Black does not have  13...Nd4  . }
12... e5 13. d5 Nb8
{ Our knight is forced back, but we will activate it again later. Here, and on the next couple of moves, White can take the pawn on c7. However, by doing so, White could face a strong initiative and therefore this is not something we should be worried about. Of course, we should know how to respond in case White does decide to take the c7-pawn, which is why I covered the capture on the next couple of moves. }
14. g3 c6
{ Undermining White's pawn on d5 right away, so our knight can get access to the c6-square again. }
15. Bg2 cxd5 16. Rxd5 Nc6 17. O-O Be6
{ Black's pieces become active, which gives us a fine game here. } *

