[White "5) Classical Variation 4.Qc2 d5 5.cxd5"]
[Black "Classical Variation 4.Qc2 − 6.Nf3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2
{ The Classical Variation of the Nimzo. The idea behind this move is twofold: White enables the recapture on c3 with the queen and can therefore keep the structure intact. Furthermore, with this move, White also enables the move e4. }
4... d5
{ I recommend this move, as I would like to avoid the lines starting with  4...O-O  5.e4  . This gives White the additional option of @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/1bPP4/2N5/PPQ1PPPP/R1B1KBNR w KQkq d6 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.cxd5  , but those lines actually work out quite nicely for Black, as I will offer you a combative antidote. }
5. cxd5 exd5 6. Nf3 c5
{ Again, we are going to put pressure on White's center right away. } 7. Bg5
O-O 8. dxc5
{ If White tries to outsmart us and prepare dxc5 by playing  8.Rd1  first, we have an abundance of suitable options. Black can already choose between  8...h6  9.Bxf6  Qxf6  10.dxc5  Bf5  11.Qb3  Nc6  followed by ...a5 and playing for initiative,  or the more positional @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp3ppp/5n2/2pp2B1/1b1P4/2N2N2/PPQ1PPPP/3RKB1R b K - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...c4  , where our moves are simple to execute  but very effective: ...h6, ...Nc6, ...Re8, ...g5, ...b5, etc. Black is better. }
8... h6
{ The most accurate continuation. We do not mind the trade on f6, and if White plays Bh4, we will be able to break the pin later with a potential ...g5. }
9. Bh4
{ The trade on f6 is something we should almost never be worried about, as it gives us the bishop pair and it will bring out our queen to an active square. Furthermore,  9.Bxf6  will likely transpose to one of the other lines. After  9...Qxf6  , White's best move here is  10.e3  , which transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp3ppp/5n2/2pp2B1/1b1P4/2N2N2/PPQ1PPPP/R3KB1R w KQ - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8.e3  h6  9.Bxf6  Qxf6  10.dxc5  . }
9... Nbd7
{ The most accurate continuation since  9...g5  10.Bg3  and only now  10...Nbd7  allows White the unnecessary option of  11.Bd6  .  Also, we should not rush to regain the pawn on c5 with our bishop. Instead, we continue our development and aim to take it with our knight. }
10. e3 g5 { Breaking the pin so we can play ...Nfe4 in the near future. } 11.
Bg3 Nxc5 12. Be2 Nfe4
{ Putting pressure on White's knight on c3 and enabling the move ...Bf5. We often have to give up the bishop for the knight on c3, but our activity and White's weak pawn on c3 will more than compensate for that.   If White tries to prevent ...Bf5 with  13.Nd4  , Black is spoiled for choice.  13...Qa5  and  taking on c3 leads to a long and forcing variation, but we have plenty of other good options. For instance, after  13...Qf6  14.O-O  Bxc3  15.bxc3  , Black has a myriad of possibilities:  15...Bf5  ,  15...Re8  , or  15...Be6  are all valid continuations.  But also @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp3p2/7p/2np2p1/1b1Nn3/2N1P1B1/PPQ1BPPP/R3K2R b KQ - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Bxc3+  14.bxc3  Bd7  followed by ...Rc8 is a viable setup. With so many choices and resources, I wouldn't put this position on our list of worries. }
*

