{ If White tries to outsmart us and prepare dxc5 by playing  8.Rd1  first, we have an abundance of suitable options. Black can already choose between  8...h6  9.Bxf6  Qxf6  10.dxc5  Bf5  11.Qb3  Nc6  followed by ...a5 and playing for initiative,  or the more positional @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp3ppp/5n2/2pp2B1/1b1P4/2N2N2/PPQ1PPPP/3RKB1R b K - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...c4  , where our moves are simple to execute  but very effective: ...h6, ...Nc6, ...Re8, ...g5, ...b5, etc. Black is better. }
8... h6 { Forcing White to make a decision with their dark-squared bishop. } 9.
Bxf6 Qxf6
{ The trade on f6 is not something we should be worried about, as we are now able to develop our bishop to f5. }
10. a3
{ With this move, White aims to neutralize our bishop pair. However, before we trade on c3, we should first activate our other bishop.   If White decides to take the pawn on c5 with  10.dxc5  ,  we should aim to recapture it with our knight:  10...Nd7=  .  Next, we will regain the pawn on c5 with a comfortable game. We will follow up by developing our light-squared bishop, preferably to f5, and we will often opt for ...Bxc3 to give White a weak pawn on c3. }
10... Bf5 { Developing with tempo is rarely a bad idea. } 11. Bd3 Bxc3+ 12.
bxc3 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Nd7
{ Black has absolutely nothing to worry about here and is already slightly for choice. }
