1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2
{ The Classical Variation of the Nimzo. The idea behind this move is twofold: White enables the recapture on c3 with the queen and can therefore keep the structure intact. Furthermore, with this move, White also enables the move e4. }
4... d5
{ I recommend this move, as I would like to avoid the lines starting with  4...O-O  5.e4  . This gives White the additional option of @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/1bPP4/2N5/PPQ1PPPP/R1B1KBNR w KQkq d6 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.cxd5  , but those lines actually work out quite nicely for Black, as I will offer you a combative antidote. }
5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4
{ Played by a couple of strong players, including Mamedyarov and Caruana. However, there are not many lines we have to know here and Black is completely fine in all of them. }
6... c5
{ Since White has not played @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2ppp/5n2/3p4/1b1P4/2N5/PPQ1PPPP/R1B1KBNR w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bg5  and pinned our knight, it is easier to strike in the center now. }
7. dxc5 Nc6 8. Nf3 d4 9. O-O-O O-O 10. Nb5
{ 10.e3  just transposes to the main line. } 10... Qa5
{ Attacking the knight on b5 and the pawn on a2. We will not be able to regain our pawn, but we will be able to develop a strong initiative in exchange for it. }
11. e3
{ Going after the a8-rook with  11.Nc7?  is short-sighted. Black can calmly play  11...Bxc5  , ignoring White's threat since the  king on c1 is a bigger fish to grill.  After  12.Nxa8  , we get in return a lethal initiative:  12...Nb4  13.Bd2  Be6-+  .  White cannot parry all of Black's ideas connected to the multiple Achilles' heel  (s)  on c1, a2, and a8.  For instance,  14.a3  is met by  14...Rc8!  when Black is winning. }
11... Qxa2
{ White's king is starting to get exposed, and we certainly have sufficient compensation for the sacrificed pawn. For example, after  12.Nfxd4  , we can already force a draw with  12...Bxc5  13.Qxc5  Qa1+  14.Kc2  Qa4+  , or continue playing: @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/pp3ppp/2n2n2/1NP5/1b1N1B2/4P3/qPQ2PPP/2KR1B1R b - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Nxd4  13.Rxd4   If White takes with the pawn on d4,  13.exd4  Be6  14.Nc3  Qa5  ,  our ...b6 idea and the strong initiative are not so easy to deal with.  13...Qa1+  14.Qb1  Qxb1+  15.Kxb1  Bxc5  , when we restored the material balance and the endgame is a pleasant one for Black. }
