[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2
{ The Classical Variation of the Nimzo. The idea behind this move is twofold: White enables the recapture on c3 with the queen and can therefore keep the structure intact. Furthermore, with this move, White also enables the move e4. }
4... d5
{ I recommend this move, as I would like to avoid the lines starting with  4...O-O  5.e4  . This gives White the additional option of @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/1bPP4/2N5/PPQ1PPPP/R1B1KBNR w KQkq d6 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.cxd5  , but those lines actually work out quite nicely for Black, as I will offer you a combative antidote. }
5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5
{ This is White’s critical continuation. By pinning the knight on f6, White makes it more difficult for us to break in the center with ...c5. However, we have another effective way to generate counterplay. }
6... h6 7. Bxf6
{ This move is quite innocuous and we should not be worried about it. White generally plays this if they want to chicken out of the complications that would arise after  7.Bh4  . }
7... Qxf6 8. a3
{ White should play this move, as it forces us to give up our bishop pair. After any other move, White is just worse. }
8... Bxc3+ 9. Qxc3 O-O
{ We do not have to worry about Qxc7 yet, as that would leave the d4-pawn hanging. }
10. e3 c6
{ We have nothing to worry about here. Next up, we will bring out our bishop to f5 and develop our knight to d7. }
