[Round "?"]
[White "5) Classical Variation 4.Qc2 d5 5.cxd5"]
[Black "Classical Variation 4.Qc2 − 6.Bg5 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2
{ The Classical Variation of the Nimzo. The idea behind this move is twofold: White enables the recapture on c3 with the queen and can therefore keep the structure intact. Furthermore, with this move, White also enables the move e4. }
4... d5
{ I recommend this move, as I would like to avoid the lines starting with  4...O-O  5.e4  . This gives White the additional option of @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/1bPP4/2N5/PPQ1PPPP/R1B1KBNR w KQkq d6 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.cxd5  , but those lines actually work out quite nicely for Black, as I will offer you a combative antidote. }
5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5
{ This is White’s critical continuation. By pinning the knight on f6, White makes it more difficult for us to break in the center with ...c5. However, we have another effective way to generate counterplay. }
6... h6 7. Bh4 Nc6
{ Normally, I would not advise placing the knight in front of the c-pawn in this structure. However, we will soon see why this move is justified. }
8. e3 g5 { The start of our aggressive operations. } 9. Bg3 h5
{ Posing the very direct threat of ...h4. This line offers Black great chances of taking over the initiative, and many strong players with White have gone immediately wrong here. }
10. h3
{ Played by Mamedyarov against Carlsen in one of the recent Meltwater events. }
10... Ne4
{ Jumping with the knight in the middle of the board and threatening ...Nxg3 to ruin White’s pawn structure, so White is forced to move the bishop. }
11. Bh2 Qe7 { Bringing ...Nxd4 tactics in the position. } 12. Bb5
{ Pinning our knight and thus stopping ...Nxd4. } 12... Bf5
{ Activating our last minor piece and x-raying White’s queen on c2. } 13. Qb3
{ If White tries to run away from the x-ray, there are plenty of options, but I like the text move.   Dodging the pin with  13.Qc1  runs into bigger issues. After  13...O-O-O  ,  Black develops a very strong initiative given the ...g4 idea and White's unhealthy king on e1. }
13... Rh6
{ The best as it is the simplest. By defending the knight on c6, we make sure that White cannot ruin our pawn structure on the queenside with a potential Bxc6. }
14. Ne2 O-O-O
{ Black has a great initiative here and went on to win quickly in Tang-Fedoseev, chess.com 2023. }
*

