{ I recommend this move, as I would like to avoid the lines starting with  4...O-O  5.e4  . This gives White the additional option of @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/1bPP4/2N5/PPQ1PPPP/R1B1KBNR w KQkq d6 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.cxd5  , but those lines actually work out quite nicely for Black, as I will offer you a combative antidote. }
5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5
{ This is White’s critical continuation. By pinning the knight on f6, White makes it more difficult for us to break in the center with ...c5. However, we have another effective way to generate counterplay. }
6... h6 7. Bh4 Nc6
{ Normally, I would not advise placing the knight in front of the c-pawn in this structure. However, we will soon see why this move is justified. }
8. e3 g5 { The start of our aggressive operations. } 9. Bg3 h5
{ Posing the very direct threat of ...h4. This line offers Black great chances of taking over the initiative, and many strong players with White have gone immediately wrong here. }
10. Bb5 h4 11. Be5 O-O
{ At first sight, it might look a bit odd to castle kingside since we have advanced both our h- and g-pawns. However, this move does enable the move ...Nxe5, and if White castles on the kingside in the future, we could use our pawns to launch an initiative on that side of the board. }
12. Bxf6
{ This is, of course, a very simple way to deal with Black's threat of ...Nxe5. However, it gives Black a very comfortable position. }
12... Qxf6
{ We will often follow up with ...Ne7 and ...c6 to strengthen our center. Black has a comfortable game here, as we will launch an initiative on the side of the board where White eventually decides to castle. }
