5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5
{ This is White’s critical continuation. By pinning the knight on f6, White makes it more difficult for us to break in the center with ...c5. However, we have another effective way to generate counterplay. }
6... h6 7. Bh4 Nc6
{ Normally, I would not advise placing the knight in front of the c-pawn in this structure. However, we will soon see why this move is justified. }
8. e3 g5 { The start of our aggressive operations. } 9. Bg3 h5
{ Posing the very direct threat of ...h4. This line offers Black great chances of taking over the initiative, and many strong players with White have gone immediately wrong here. }
10. f3
{ This was played by Nakamura against Le Quang Liem in the 2021 Saint Louis Rapid and Blitz. However, this immediately gives Black a very comfortable position. }
10... Qe7
{ The threats of ...Qxe3+ and ...Nxd4 are quite awkward for White to deal with. }
11. O-O-O { Ignoring the threat on the e3-pawn and sacrificing two pawns. }
11... Qxe3+
{ There are other options as well, such as  11...h4  , but I like this move best, as it is the most direct. }
12. Kb1 Nxd4
{ Having said A, we should now also say B and take the second pawn on d4, attacking White's queen. It is actually White here who will have to be precise. }
13. Rxd4 { White's only move to stay in the game is this exchange sacrifice. }
13... Qxd4 { Of course, we have to recapture. } 14. Bf2
{ White's only move to keep an acceptable position. } 14... Qf4
{ The only good square for our queen, as we have to make sure that the bishop on b4 remains protected. Otherwise, White would be able to pick it up with Qa4+. Furthermore, this move enables ...Bf5, which helps us get our pieces out. }
15. Bd3
{ White's best move, as they develop the bishop and make sure that we do not have ...Bf5, which would make our life a lot easier. }
15... c6
{ We have other options as well, but they all lead to messy positions where White is fine if they know what they are doing. I like this move best, as it is the easiest. }
16. Bg3
{ This is White's only move if they do want to steer the game towards a move repetition. However, it does come with some risk, as White will be down in material. }
16... Qe3 { The best square for our queen. } 17. Nh3
{ Developing the knight and preparing Re1. } 17... Qe7
{ There are other options as well, but I like this move best, as it is the easiest. We are preparing ...Be6, so that we can get our king out of the center quickly with ...O-O-O. }
18. Nxg5 h4
{ Pushing the bishop back is a clever idea, as otherwise, White would be able to play Bh4 and create annoying pressure along the h4-d8 diagonal. }
19. Bf2 Be6 20. Re1 Nh5
{ Attacking the knight on g5. We should play this move before castling queenside.  20...O-O-O ?!  is inaccurate due to  21.Nxe6  fxe6  22.Rxe6  Qxe6  23.Bf5⩲  and White's queen will be stronger than our two rooks. }
21. Bxh4 O-O-O
{ The position is still somewhat messy, but Black is certainly not on the worse side of the complications. }
