[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3
{ The Kasparov Variation. The main idea behind this move is to see how Black will react and then proceed most appropriately to Black's response. }
4... O-O
{ Black has a lot of moves, but I like this one the most, as it is simple and flexible. }
5. Qb3
{ We will respond in the same fashion as to 4.Qb3. If White plays  5.e3  ,  we will play  5...d5  and transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  O-O  5.Nf3  d5  .   5.Bd2  is also likely to transpose to the 4.e3 system, as here we play  5...d5  and White's best move is  6.e3  .   In case White plays  5.Qc2  ,  we will play  5...d5  and transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qc2  d5  5.Nf3  O-O  . }
5... c5 { Defending the bishop on b4 and exerting pressure on White's center. }
6. dxc5
{ Played by no less than Magnus Carlsen against Wesley So in one of the online chess24 tournaments. }
6... Na6
{ Without the inclusion of Nf3 and ...O-O, we would respond with ...Nc6, but here we should react slightly differently. Our idea is again to play ...Ne4, to either damage White's pawn structure, or acquire the bishop pair in case White plays Bd2. }
7. Bd2
{ This is what Magnus played in the aforementioned game and it makes a lot of sense, as it prevents us from playing ...Ne4. However, we have another clever way to proceed here. }
7... Qe7
{ Our idea is to play ...Nxc5 on the next move since Qxb4 will run into ...Nd3+ with a discovery check on the queen. }
8. g3
{ After  8.a3  ,  we will have to respond differently, as ...Nxc5 does not work anymore; the queen on b4 will be protected by the a3-pawn. Following  8...Bxc3  9.Qxc3  Nxc5=  ,  White may have the bishop pair, but we have an excellent game due to our lead in development. Next, we are going to play ...b6, ...Bb7, and ...Rac8, as we can try to target the pawn on c4. }
8... Nxc5 9. Qc2
{ As mentioned before, White cannot take our bishop since  9.Qxb4??  runs into  9...Nd3+  10.exd3  Qxb4-+  . }
9... b6
{ Black is already slightly for choice, as we have excellent piece play here. Next, we are going to play ...Bb7 followed by ...Rac8. }
