1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3
{ The Kasparov Variation. The main idea behind this move is to see how Black will react and then proceed most appropriately to Black's response. }
4... O-O
{ Black has a lot of moves, but I like this one the most, as it is simple and flexible. }
5. Qb3
{ We will respond in the same fashion as to 4.Qb3. If White plays  5.e3  ,  we will play  5...d5  and transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  O-O  5.Nf3  d5  .   5.Bd2  is also likely to transpose to the 4.e3 system, as here we play  5...d5  and White's best move is  6.e3  .   In case White plays  5.Qc2  ,  we will play  5...d5  and transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qc2  d5  5.Nf3  O-O  . }
5... c5 { Defending the bishop on b4 and exerting pressure on White's center. }
6. Bg5
{ Pinning the knight on f6 with the bishop is White's most testing move. } 6...
h6
{ If White plays Bg5, it's almost always a good idea to play ...h6 to push the bishop back a bit. We also do not mind the trade on f6, as we would get the bishop pair, and our queen would be developed. }
7. Bh4 Nc6
{ Developing the knight and increasing the pressure on White's center. } 8. e3
{ 8.d5  runs into  8...Na5  and  the c4-pawn will be taken next  , while @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1p1pp1/2n1pn1p/2p5/1bPP3B/1QN2N2/PP2PPPP/R3KB1R w KQ - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.O-O-O  can be met by  8...Nxd4  9.Nxd4  cxd4  10.Rxd4  @@StartBracket@@In case of  10.Qxb4  dxc3  11.Qxc3  , we have  11...Ne4  , with a preferable position.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1p1pp1/4pn1p/8/1bPR3B/1QN5/PP2PPPP/2K2B1R b - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...e5  11.Rd1  Bxc3  12.Qxc3  d6  .  Black's position is already easier to play since we have ideas such as ...Be6, ...Qe7, ...Ne4, depending on how White decides to continue development. }
8... cxd4
{ It is generally a good idea to go for this trade. We want to follow up with ...d5 in the foreseeable future, so that we can give White an isolated pawn on d4 with ...dxc4. }
9. Nxd4
{ If White goes for  9.exd4  ,  we can play  9...d5  right away, which gives us a comfortable game, as we are going to play ...dxc4 soon, to give White an isolated pawn on d4.   In case White tries to escape the isolani by closing the center with  10.c5  , we can always be on the lookout  for ...e5, ...g5-g4, and ...b6 ideas, depending on the circumstances. In this specific case, White's plan fails tactically in vie of  10...g5  11.Bg3  g4  12.Ne5  Nxd4  13.Qd1  Nf5  , when Black has a significant advantage according to the engine. }
9... Nxd4 10. exd4
{ Of course, White cannot grab the bishop pair with  10.Qxb4??  ,  as that runs into  10...Nc2+  and we win the queen. }
10... Be7
{ Escaping the threat of White's queen and neutralizing White's pin on our knight. Black has a fine game here. Next, we will play ...b6, ...Bb7, and ...d5, in order to play ...dxc4 and give White an isolated pawn on d4. }
