1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3
{ The Kasparov Variation. The main idea behind this move is to see how Black will react and then proceed most appropriately to Black's response. }
4... O-O
{ Black has a lot of moves, but I like this one the most, as it is simple and flexible. }
5. Bg5
{ Now that Black has castled, this move gains in strength, as playing ...h6 and ...g5 has somewhat lost its appeal since that would always weaken the black king.   If White plays  5.e3  ,  we will play  5...d5  and transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.e3  O-O  5.Nf3  d5  .   5.Bd2  is also likely to transpose to the 4.e3 system, as here we play  5...d5  and White's best move is  6.e3  .   In case White plays  5.Qc2  ,  we will play  5...d5  and transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Qc2  d5  5.Nf3  O-O  . }
5... c5 { We should exert pressure on White's center as quickly as possible. }
6. Rc1
{ With this move, White enables the recapture with the rook on c3, keeping the structure intact.   6.Qb3  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQ - 4 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qb3  c5  6.Bg5  . }
6... cxd4 7. Nxd4
