6. Rc1
{ With this move, White enables the recapture with the rook on c3, keeping the structure intact.   6.Qb3  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQ - 4 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Qb3  c5  6.Bg5  . }
6... cxd4 7. Nxd4
{ Taking with the queen on d4 allows us to develop with tempo:  7.Qxd4  Nc6  and the queen has to move again. }
7... h6
{ As we will often see in this opening, ...h6 will almost always be a good way to meet Bg5. We do not mind the trade on f6, and the inclusion of ...h6 and Bh4 favors us somewhat. We will have an escape square for our king, and we can potentially break the pin with ...g5 as well. }
8. Bh4 d5
{ It is a good idea to strike in the center, as White is still quite far from getting castled. }
9. cxd5
{ This leads to the sharpest lines.   9.a3?  gets punished by  9...Bxc3+  10.Rxc3  e5  11.Nb3  d4  and Black has a significant advantage. }
