{ Exerting pressure on the c4-pawn in typical Benko style. White's best choice is to decline any immediate pawn sacrifices, as Black will get a big initiative.   5...d6  is also fine, as after  6.e4  b5  ,  we transpose to the main line. }
6. e4 { Defending the pawn on c4. } 6... d6
{ Stopping White's e5 push. Here White has a lot of options, but against all of them, we get a good game and also get our chances to take over the initiative. }
7. cxb5
{ Played three times by Arjun Erigaisi at the 2022 World Rapid and Blitz Championships. }
7... exd5 8. exd5 Nbd7 { An interesting move that has not been played before. }
9. Bd3 c4
{ We sacrifice this pawn to open up the g1-a7 diagonal for our bishop or queen so we have more attacking potential. Furthermore, if White decides to take this pawn, we can gain a tempo on the bishop with our knight. }
10. Bxc4 Ne5
{ Black has a big lead in development and great attacking potential, as White's king will struggle to make it out of the center. }
