12... exd5
{ If White does not take on e6, we should take on d5 ourselves. White now has to decide whether to take with the pawn on d5  (with or without the inclusion of Nxd5)  or take with the knight and the queen. In both cases, we have plenty of play and a fine game. }
13. Bg5 { Pinning our knight on f6. We have to be somewhat careful here. }
13... Nc7
{ We don't want to let White recapture on d5 with the knight unopposed. Furthermore, both  13...d4  14.Nd5  and @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/p4ppp/n2p1n2/b1pp2B1/4P3/P1N2P2/1P2N1PP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13...dxe4  14.fxe4  gives White a dangerous initiative against our king. }
14. exd5
{ 14.Nxd5  Ncxd5  15.exd5  gives us a better version of the main line, as White’s knight on c3 is somewhat more active than our knight on c7. }
14... h6 15. Bh4 Re8
{ Black has a fine game, as the pawns on d5 and b2 are somewhat weak. Next, we will continue activating our pieces with ...Rb8. }
