[Black "Nimzo-Indian 4.f3 − 7.Nge2 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3
{ The idea behind this move is quite simple − White wants to build a big center by going e4 quickly. Subsequently, White often tries to use the center to go for an attack on the kingside.  White players usually choose this move when they have aggressive intentions as opposed to trying to get a small edge and playing a risk-free game. This is because Black has lots of different ways to respond to this line.  I am going to recommend a line that has not been played yet at the top level, but it solves Black's problems and gives us the double-edged game that we are looking for. }
4... c5
{ Challenging White's center right away. Furthermore, this move enables ...Qa5, which exerts pressure on the c3-knight. }
5. d5
{ Practically the only move if White wants to keep their hopes of an advantage and not get a worse position immediately.   If White plays  5.a3  , we will transpose to the Sämisch Variation after  5...Bxc3+  6.bxc3  . }
5... b5
{ Exerting pressure on the c4-pawn in typical Benko style. White's best choice is to decline any immediate pawn sacrifices, as Black will get a big initiative.   5...d6  is also fine, as after  6.e4  b5  ,  we transpose to the main line. }
6. e4 { Defending the pawn on c4. } 6... d6
{ Stopping White's e5 push. Here White has a lot of options, but against all of them, we get a good game and also get our chances to take over the initiative. }
7. Ne2
{ Historically, this has been the main continuation in this position. However, these days, it is effectively neutralized by the strongest engines. White is sacrificing the pawn on c4 but hopes to get it back sometime in the future. }
7... bxc4 8. Nf4 e5
{ The most straightforward way for Black to get a good position.   8...g5  9.Nfe2  exd5  10.exd5  Qe7  is possible as well, and it has been played by Wesley So and Ding recently, but it leads to wild complications. I like the text better because it is much simpler. }
9. Ne2
{ Unfortunately for White, the knight is forced to retreat on e2 and now blocks the bishop again. This gives us time to defend the pawn on c4. }
9... Nbd7 10. Ng3
{ If White plays  10.a3  , we will just play  10...Ba5  and not much changes compared to the main lines. }
10... Nb6 { We are just in time to defend the pawn. } 11. Be2 Ng8
{ An excellent regrouping move. The knight is headed to e7, where it will be better placed. First of all, the knight can never get pinned by a potential Bg5, it also supports the potential ...f5 break, and in the event of @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/p3nppp/1n1p4/2pPp3/1bp1P3/2N2PN1/PP2B1PP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 8 13@@EndFEN@@  13.f4  exf4  14.Bxf4  ,  we can challenge White's bishop on f4 right away with  14...Ng6  . }
12. h4
{ This is Cheparinov's suggestion. White's idea is to play h5-h6 to create weaknesses on our kingside. Furthermore, even if we stop White from playing h6 by going ...h6 ourselves, the pawn on h5 prevents us from playing ...Ng6 in the event of a potential f4 exf4 Bxf4. }
12... Ne7
{ There are other options as well, but for simplicity's sake, I suggest we just stick to the same plan. }
13. h5 { White continues with their plan on the kingside. } 13... h6
{ We do not want to let White play h6, as that would create too many weak squares on the kingside. }
14. f4
{ As mentioned before, since White has advanced the pawn to h5, we now cannot meet this move with  14...exf4  15.Bxf4  Ng6  . Therefore, we should look for other ways to activate our pieces. }
14... O-O 15. O-O Kh8
{ We are now preparing to strike back with ...f5, as our king will always be sitting better on h8 than on g8, where there will never be any checks on the a2-g8 diagonal. }
16. Be3
{ White can stop us from playing ...f5 altogether with  16.f5  , but here we have an even better way to stop White from playing f6 with  16...Ng8  .  With our knight coming to f6, it will be quite difficult for White to do anything on the kingside. Meanwhile, we are going to create counterplay on the queenside. }
16... f5
{ Striking back in the center. Black has a good game here, as we are still up a pawn and we have plenty of activity. }
