[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Nimzo-Indian 4.f3"]
[Black "Nimzo-Indian 4.f3 − 7.Bd2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3
{ The idea behind this move is quite simple − White wants to build a big center by going e4 quickly. Subsequently, White often tries to use the center to go for an attack on the kingside.  White players usually choose this move when they have aggressive intentions as opposed to trying to get a small edge and playing a risk-free game. This is because Black has lots of different ways to respond to this line.  I am going to recommend a line that has not been played yet at the top level, but it solves Black's problems and gives us the double-edged game that we are looking for. }
4... c5
{ Challenging White's center right away. Furthermore, this move enables ...Qa5, which exerts pressure on the c3-knight. }
5. d5
{ Practically the only move if White wants to keep their hopes of an advantage and not get a worse position immediately.   If White plays  5.a3  , we will transpose to the Sämisch Variation after  5...Bxc3+  6.bxc3  . }
5... b5
{ Exerting pressure on the c4-pawn in typical Benko style. White's best choice is to decline any immediate pawn sacrifices, as Black will get a big initiative.   5...d6  is also fine, as after  6.e4  b5  ,  we transpose to the main line. }
6. e4 { Defending the pawn on c4. } 6... d6
{ Stopping White's e5 push. Here White has a lot of options, but against all of them, we get a good game and also get our chances to take over the initiative. }
7. Bd2 { Unpinning the knight on c3, so now Nxb5 becomes a threat. } 7... a6
{ Defending the pawn on b5 and insisting on a pawn sacrifice. It is still  White's best choice to not accept the pawn sacrifice. }
8. dxe6
{ If White does decide to go for the pawn sacrifice, this is the best way of doing so. }
8... Bxe6 { Recapturing the pawn and developing the bishop at the same time. }
9. cxb5
{ White should take the pawn, as otherwise, the last move does not make any sense. }
9... O-O
{ Just continuing our development. We are getting ready to break in the center now with ...d5 while White is struggling to get their pieces out. }
10. Nge2
{ White's best approach is to get their pieces out quickly and not hang on to the pawn. It is inadvisable to be greedy and take another pawn with  10.bxa6  , as after  10...d5⩱  , we are breaking open the center while White is still underdeveloped. }
10... axb5
{ At least temporarily regaining the pawn, and now our knight can develop to the c6-square. }
11. Nf4
{ Again, it is White's best approach to continue development and not hang on to the extra pawn. With this move, White also enables Bxb5, taking the pawn and developing at the same time. In case White does hang on to the extra pawn with  11.Nxb5  , we will get play after  11...Nc6∓  ,  as ...Qb6 is coming quickly and White has serious difficulty completing development. }
11... Bxc3
{ It might seem somewhat unnatural to voluntarily trade the bishop for the knight, but we should do so now, as in this position, White cannot comfortably recapture with the bishop. }
12. Bxc3 b4
{ The point − the bishop either has to trade itself for the knight or retreat passively. }
13. Nxe6
{ The start of a trading sequence, which simplifies the position, but also does not fully solve White's problems.  13.Bd2  Nc6∓  is also comfortably better for Black. }
13... fxe6 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Bc4
{ Developing the bishop and eyeing the pawn on e6, so Black cannot take the b2-pawn for free. }
15... Qe5 { We have a pleasant advantage as ...Nc6-d4 is coming quickly. } *

