1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3
{ The Sämisch Variation of the Nimzo. With this move, White forces us to trade on c3, and White acquires the bishop pair right away. The drawback of this variation is that it doubles White's pawns, especially the pawn on c4, which can become a serious weakness.  Black's plan will be to exert a lot of pressure on the c4-pawn by going ...c5, ...Nc6, ...b6, ...Na5, and ...Ba6. White, on the other hand, will try to build up a big center with moves like f3 and e4, and potentially try to use the central advantage to launch an attack on the kingside. Therefore, we should delay castling here for a bit. }
4... Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5
{ Our idea here is to follow up with ...Nc6, specifically to make it difficult for White to play e4 followed by Bd3. After that, our plan will usually be to continue with ...d6, ...b6, ...Na5, and ...Ba6 to exert pressure on the c4-pawn. }
6. e3 b6
{ Since d4 is firmly defended, we should delay ...Nc6 and instead play this move to harass White's development in another way. }
7. Bd3 Bb7
{ Stopping White from playing e4 and attacking the pawn on g2, which forces White to make a slightly awkward move. }
8. f3 Nc6 9. Nh3
{ A possible move, but its drawback is that now the knight does not protect the pawn on d4, and it will be difficult for White to get e3-e4 in. }
9... d6 { Keeping our options open. } 10. O-O Qe7 11. Bb2
{ Protecting the pawn on d4 once more and thus preparing e3-e4. Here we have a nice way to render White's play in the center and on the kingside useless. }
11... O-O-O
{ Our king is actually quite safe on the queenside. We can proceed with moving one of our rooks to g8, followed by ...g5. Furthermore, ...Kb8 is never a bad move, to tuck the king in a bit more, and we will want to meet a potential e4 with ...e5.  Lastly, we want to make sure that White does not get a4-a5 in by keeping our knight on c6 and potentially moving it to a5, to firmly block the advance. }
