[Black "Sämisch Variation 4.a3 − 6.f3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3
{ The Sämisch Variation of the Nimzo. With this move, White forces us to trade on c3, and White acquires the bishop pair right away. The drawback of this variation is that it doubles White's pawns, especially the pawn on c4, which can become a serious weakness.  Black's plan will be to exert a lot of pressure on the c4-pawn by going ...c5, ...Nc6, ...b6, ...Na5, and ...Ba6. White, on the other hand, will try to build up a big center with moves like f3 and e4, and potentially try to use the central advantage to launch an attack on the kingside. Therefore, we should delay castling here for a bit. }
4... Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5
{ Our idea here is to follow up with ...Nc6, specifically to make it difficult for White to play e4 followed by Bd3. After that, our plan will usually be to continue with ...d6, ...b6, ...Na5, and ...Ba6 to exert pressure on the c4-pawn. }
6. f3 Nc6 7. e4 d6
{ Stopping e5. By playing ...Nc6 quickly, we have prevented White from playing 8.Bd3 here as that would hang the pawn on d4. }
8. d5
{ This is one of the ways White can deal with the pressure on the d4-pawn. }
8... Na5
{ The best square for the knight, as it exerts pressure on the c4-pawn.  8...Ne5  would not be as effective because the knight can always get kicked away with f4. }
9. Bd3 b6
{ Continuing our usual plan. We want to develop the bishop to a6 and go after White’s c4-pawn. }
10. Ne2 Ba6 11. O-O Qe7
{ White is planning to launch an initiative on the kingside, but fortunately, we have a clever way of dealing with this. The queen is placed slightly better on e7 than on d7, as White cannot try to damage our pawn structure with Bg5xf6.   The reason why  11...O-O  is so dangerous is because it gives White the opportunity to play  12.Bg5  . Breaking the pin now with  12...h6  and ...g5 severely weakens our king, but if we do not do this, White is going to play f4 followed by e5 or Ng3-h5 with a serious attack. }
12. Ng3
{ 12.Bg5  can be met with the same  12...O-O-O  , after which the  bishop on g5 can be chased away with ...h6. It is unclear what the bishop move to g5 actually achieves. }
12... O-O-O
{ Our king sits perfectly safe on this side of the board. The pawn on c4 is terribly weak, and sooner or later we are going to collect it. }
