[White "8) Sämisch Variation 4.a3"]
[Black "Sämisch Variation 4.a3 − 6.f3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3
{ The Sämisch Variation of the Nimzo. With this move, White forces us to trade on c3, and White acquires the bishop pair right away. The drawback of this variation is that it doubles White's pawns, especially the pawn on c4, which can become a serious weakness.  Black's plan will be to exert a lot of pressure on the c4-pawn by going ...c5, ...Nc6, ...b6, ...Na5, and ...Ba6. White, on the other hand, will try to build up a big center with moves like f3 and e4, and potentially try to use the central advantage to launch an attack on the kingside. Therefore, we should delay castling here for a bit. }
4... Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5
{ Our idea here is to follow up with ...Nc6, specifically to make it difficult for White to play e4 followed by Bd3. After that, our plan will usually be to continue with ...d6, ...b6, ...Na5, and ...Ba6 to exert pressure on the c4-pawn. }
6. f3 Nc6 7. e4 d6
{ Stopping e5. By playing ...Nc6 quickly, we have prevented White from playing 8.Bd3 here as that would hang the pawn on d4. }
8. Ne2 b6 9. Bg5
{ This is Ivan Sokolov's recommendation in his course Take Down the Nimzo-Indian. }
9... h6
{ As we will see in many variations, it is almost always a good idea to meet Bg5 with ...h6, to push White's bishop a bit. }
10. Bh4 O-O
{ We should castle first as  10...Ba6  runs into  11.Qa4  and White wins a piece. }
11. Nc1
{ This might look passive, but the idea is to move the knight to b3 so that we cannot play ...Na5 to exert more pressure on White's c4-pawn. }
11... Ba6 12. Nb3
{ Now that White's knight has landed on b3 and stops ...Na5, we have to look for other ways to exert pressure on the c4-pawn. }
12... Rc8 { Placing the rook on the c-file; we are now preparing ...cxd4. } 13.
Be2 cxd4 { Opening up the file for our rook. } 14. cxd4 Ne7
{ Moving the knight out of the way to attack the c4-pawn. It might seem somewhat counterintuitive to allow White to take on f6. However, this is the best square for the knight and our king will still be quite safe. }
15. Bxf6
{ White should take advantage of the opportunity to ruin our pawn structure in front of our king now, as otherwise, we would have ...Ng6 on the next move. }
15... gxf6 16. Nd2
{ This is White's best way to defend the c4-pawn. If White defends the pawn with  16.Rc1  ,  we will continue with  16...Ng6⇆  ,  which gives Black a fine game. In the event of  17.O-O  , we want to play  17...Nf4  and we also have the ...f5 and ...d5 breaks to exert pressure on White's center. }
16... d5
{ An excellent move to break up White's center.  16...Nc6  is possible as well. }
17. cxd5 { White's only move to maintain the balance. } 17... Bxe2 18. Qxe2
exd5 { Now ...dxe4 is a threat, after which the d4-pawn would be hanging. } 19.
O-O { White decides to sacrifice the pawn. } 19... dxe4 20. Nxe4
{ The gift on d4 is not something we should be worried about. } 20... Qxd4+ 21.
Kh1 Rfd8 { The onus will be on White here to prove the compensation. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Sämisch Variation 4.a3"]
[Black "Sämisch Variation 4.a3 − 6.f3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3
{ The Sämisch Variation of the Nimzo. With this move, White forces us to trade on c3, and White acquires the bishop pair right away. The drawback of this variation is that it doubles White's pawns, especially the pawn on c4, which can become a serious weakness.  Black's plan will be to exert a lot of pressure on the c4-pawn by going ...c5, ...Nc6, ...b6, ...Na5, and ...Ba6. White, on the other hand, will try to build up a big center with moves like f3 and e4, and potentially try to use the central advantage to launch an attack on the kingside. Therefore, we should delay castling here for a bit. }
4... Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5
{ Our idea here is to follow up with ...Nc6, specifically to make it difficult for White to play e4 followed by Bd3. After that, our plan will usually be to continue with ...d6, ...b6, ...Na5, and ...Ba6 to exert pressure on the c4-pawn. }
6. f3 Nc6 7. e4 d6
{ Stopping e5. By playing ...Nc6 quickly, we have prevented White from playing 8.Bd3 here as that would hang the pawn on d4. }
8. Ne2 b6 9. Bg5
{ This is Ivan Sokolov's recommendation in his course Take Down the Nimzo-Indian. }
9... h6
{ As we will see in many variations, it is almost always a good idea to meet Bg5 with ...h6, to push White's bishop a bit. }
10. Bh4 O-O
{ We should castle first as  10...Ba6  runs into  11.Qa4  and White wins a piece. }
11. Nc1
{ This might look passive, but the idea is to move the knight to b3 so that we cannot play ...Na5 to exert more pressure on White's c4-pawn. }
11... Ba6 12. Nb3
{ Now that White's knight has landed on b3 and stops ...Na5, we have to look for other ways to exert pressure on the c4-pawn. }
12... Rc8 { Placing the rook on the c-file; we are now preparing ...cxd4. } 13.
Be2 cxd4 { Opening up the file for our rook. } 14. cxd4 Ne7
{ Moving the knight out of the way to attack the c4-pawn. It might seem somewhat counterintuitive to allow White to take on f6. However, this is the best square for the knight and our king will still be quite safe. }
15. Bxf6
{ White should take advantage of the opportunity to ruin our pawn structure in front of our king now, as otherwise, we would have ...Ng6 on the next move. }
15... gxf6 16. Nd2
{ This is White's best way to defend the c4-pawn. If White defends the pawn with  16.Rc1  ,  we will continue with  16...Ng6⇆  ,  which gives Black a fine game. In the event of  17.O-O  , we want to play  17...Nf4  and we also have the ...f5 and ...d5 breaks to exert pressure on White's center. }
16... d5
{ An excellent move to break up White's center.  16...Nc6  is possible as well. }
17. cxd5 { White's only move to maintain the balance. } 17... Bxe2 18. Qxe2
exd5 { Now ...dxe4 is a threat, after which the d4-pawn would be hanging. } 19.
Qe3
{ Defending the pawn on d4 and attacking the pawn on h6. Fortunately, we have a clever way to solve our problems. }
19... Nf5 { Sacrificing the knight, but we will get the piece back shortly. }
20. exf5 Re8
{ This is the point behind the knight sacrifice. White is forced to give back the piece. }
21. Ne4 { White's only move. } 21... dxe4 22. fxe4 Qe7
{ Next up, we will take on e4, after which White will have to fight for equality. }
*

