[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3
{ The Sämisch Variation of the Nimzo. With this move, White forces us to trade on c3, and White acquires the bishop pair right away. The drawback of this variation is that it doubles White's pawns, especially the pawn on c4, which can become a serious weakness.  Black's plan will be to exert a lot of pressure on the c4-pawn by going ...c5, ...Nc6, ...b6, ...Na5, and ...Ba6. White, on the other hand, will try to build up a big center with moves like f3 and e4, and potentially try to use the central advantage to launch an attack on the kingside. Therefore, we should delay castling here for a bit. }
4... Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5
{ Our idea here is to follow up with ...Nc6, specifically to make it difficult for White to play e4 followed by Bd3. After that, our plan will usually be to continue with ...d6, ...b6, ...Na5, and ...Ba6 to exert pressure on the c4-pawn. }
6. f3 Nc6 7. e4 d6
{ Stopping e5. By playing ...Nc6 quickly, we have prevented White from playing 8.Bd3 here as that would hang the pawn on d4. }
8. Be3
{ Giri had two games recently against Praggnanandhaa, and he played this move in the second one. Furthermore, it has been played in a lot of games by Salem who is an expert in this variation. }
8... b6 9. Bd3 Na5 10. Ne2 Ba6
{ Putting a lot of pressure on the c4-pawn. White does not have a good way of defending this pawn and often ends up sacrificing it. Note that we cannot take the pawn on the next move, as White will always have Qa4+ tactics. }
11. O-O Qc7
{ The best move and also the most clear-cut. This was also played by Jeffery Xiong in a recent blitz match against Salem. The queen is well placed on c7, as we can often use it to generate counterplay on the queenside after we have grabbed the pawn on c4.   11...Nd7  was played by Praggnanandhaa against Giri, but after  12.f4  Bxc4  13.f5  ,  the position becomes quite messy. I like the text better, as it seems more clear-cut. }
12. Ng3 O-O
{ Now that we are castled, we are going to take the pawn on c4 on the next move. }
13. f4
{ White cannot hang on to the pawn on c4, so the best way forward is to just sacrifice it and try to launch an initiative on the kingside. }
13... Bxc4
{ We generally want to take with our bishop on c4, as the exchange of light-squared bishops takes the sting out of White’s attack on the kingside. }
14. f5
{ White just goes on with their play on the kingside. Fortunately, there are no real threats, so we should continue generating counterplay on the queenside. }
14... Bxd3
{ As mentioned before, we want to trade off these bishops, as it seriously limits White’s attacking potential. }
15. Qxd3 cxd4
{ Finally, it is the right time to trade, as we can use the c-file to generate counterplay. }
16. cxd4 Qc4
{ The point of ...Qc7. We are creating counterplay on the queenside, and White has not achieved anything tangible yet on the kingside. }
