[White "9) Fianchetto Variation 4.g3"]
[Black "Fianchetto Variation 4.g3 − 6.cxd5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3
{ The g3-System, which can also be referred to as the Romanishin Variation, turns the game into somewhat of a hybrid of the Catalan and the Nimzo. In this line, we will go for a quick ...d5 and ...dxc4. It will be difficult for White to get the pawn back, as their knight on c3 will always be in the way of a potential Qc2xc4. }
4... O-O
{ Playing  4...d5  first is fine as well.  5.Bg2  O-O  and we transpose to the main line. But not  5...dxc4??  as this loses a piece after  6.Qa4++-  . }
5. Bg2 d5
{ Our best approach is to place this pawn in the center and take on c4 quickly, as it will actually be difficult for White to get the pawn back. }
6. cxd5 { Taking on d5 is quite toothless. } 6... exd5
{ Black always has a good Carlsbad structure due to White's blunted bishop on g2. Next, we are going to play ...c6 and ... Re8, and Black's play is already somewhat easier. }
*

