1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3
{ The g3-System, which can also be referred to as the Romanishin Variation, turns the game into somewhat of a hybrid of the Catalan and the Nimzo. In this line, we will go for a quick ...d5 and ...dxc4. It will be difficult for White to get the pawn back, as their knight on c3 will always be in the way of a potential Qc2xc4. }
4... O-O
{ Playing  4...d5  first is fine as well.  5.Bg2  O-O  and we transpose to the main line. But not  5...dxc4??  as this loses a piece after  6.Qa4++-  . }
5. Bg2 d5
{ Our best approach is to place this pawn in the center and take on c4 quickly, as it will actually be difficult for White to get the pawn back. }
6. Qb3
{ With this move, White develops the queen, attacks the bishop on b4, and exerts more pressure on the d5-pawn. However, it does neglect the development of the g1-knight to f3 and White's ability to castle. Therefore, we should challenge White's center as quickly as possible. }
6... c5 { Defending the bishop and exerting pressure on White's d4-pawn. } 7.
cxd5 exd5 8. dxc5
{ If White decides to take the pawn on c5, we will not recapture with our bishop, but instead, keep playing for swift development. }
8... Nc6
{ Defending the bishop on b4, and bringing ...d4 ideas in the position.  8...Na6  is very good for Black as well. }
9. a3 { White's best move, to try to break the pin on the c3-knight. } 9...
Bxc5
{ White's play has clearly backfired. We are going to play ...d4 quickly to disturb the harmony of White's pieces and our opponent will need to be extremely careful here.   Of course, taking the pawn on d5 would accelerate White's demise:  10.Nxd5?  Be6  11.Nxf6+  Qxf6  12.Qf3  Bf5+-  .  With ...Nd4 coming next and White's pieces still in the box, the king on e1 will have to accept the inevitable defeat. }
