1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3
{ The g3-System, which can also be referred to as the Romanishin Variation, turns the game into somewhat of a hybrid of the Catalan and the Nimzo. In this line, we will go for a quick ...d5 and ...dxc4. It will be difficult for White to get the pawn back, as their knight on c3 will always be in the way of a potential Qc2xc4. }
4... O-O
{ Playing  4...d5  first is fine as well.  5.Bg2  O-O  and we transpose to the main line. But not  5...dxc4??  as this loses a piece after  6.Qa4++-  . }
5. Bg2 d5
{ Our best approach is to place this pawn in the center and take on c4 quickly, as it will actually be difficult for White to get the pawn back. }
6. Nf3 dxc4
{ Since White has developed the bishop with g3 and Bg2, instead of with e3 and Bd3/e2, it is often a good idea to just take this pawn, as it is quite hard for White to get it back. }
7. O-O
{ If White plays  7.a3  we will just play  7...Bxc3  and transpose to the lines with the 6.a3 move order after  8.bxc3  . }
7... Nc6 { By eyeing the pawn on d4, we stop White from playing Ne5 and Qc2. }
8. Rb1
{ This has been played in a handful of games, including a game that I played with Black. The only idea behind Rb1 is that in the event of ...Bxc3 bxc3, White's rook is active on the half-open b-file. However, apart from that, this move does not do much. }
8... a6
{ This is what I played in the aforementioned game in 2014, and the strongest engines nowadays agree that it is the best move. The idea is to play ...Rb8 followed by ...b5 to hang on to the pawn on c4.   We should not start with  8...Rb8  ,  as here White has  9.a3  Be7  10.Qa4  and the difference is that the pawn on a7 will often be hanging. }
9. a3 Be7
{ We should not trade with  9...Bxc3  , as after  10.bxc3  , White's  rook on b1 will be activated, and White's d4-pawn will be strengthened. }
10. Qa4
{ This is what I faced myself. The difference with @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2ppp/2n1pn2/8/1bpP4/2N2NP1/PP2PPBP/1RBQ1RK1 b - - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Rb8  becomes clear now, as we will not have a  hanging pawn on a7, and so we can just play the text move. }
10... Nxd4
{ Grabbing another pawn. White simply does not have sufficient compensation for the sacrificed material. }
11. Nxd4 Qxd4 12. Be3 Qg4
{ It is best to keep the queen active in this position.  12...Qd8  is what I played in the game Ris-Bok, Riga 2014, and went on to win. However, the text is more accurate. }
13. h3 Qh5 14. Qxc4 { White finally regains one of the pawns. } 14... c6
{ Our opponent simply does not have enough compensation for the one pawn that White is still down. Black has an excellent game here and we can follow up with ...e5 to free our light-squared bishop. }
