[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Fianchetto Variation 4.g3"]
[Black "Fianchetto Variation 4.g3 − 6.Nf3 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3
{ The g3-System, which can also be referred to as the Romanishin Variation, turns the game into somewhat of a hybrid of the Catalan and the Nimzo. In this line, we will go for a quick ...d5 and ...dxc4. It will be difficult for White to get the pawn back, as their knight on c3 will always be in the way of a potential Qc2xc4. }
4... O-O
{ Playing  4...d5  first is fine as well.  5.Bg2  O-O  and we transpose to the main line. But not  5...dxc4??  as this loses a piece after  6.Qa4++-  . }
5. Bg2 d5
{ Our best approach is to place this pawn in the center and take on c4 quickly, as it will actually be difficult for White to get the pawn back. }
6. Nf3 dxc4
{ Since White has developed the bishop with g3 and Bg2, instead of with e3 and Bd3/e2, it is often a good idea to just take this pawn, as it is quite hard for White to get it back. }
7. O-O
{ If White plays  7.a3  we will just play  7...Bxc3  and transpose to the lines with the 6.a3 move order after  8.bxc3  . }
7... Nc6 { By eyeing the pawn on d4, we stop White from playing Ne5 and Qc2. }
8. Qa4 { White is threatening Ne5 again, which would cause serious trouble. }
8... Nd5 { Addressing the threat of Ne5 and threatening ...Nxc3. } 9. Qc2
{ Defending the knight on c3, and White wants to go e4 now. } 9... Be7
{ 10.e4  can now be comfortably met with  10...Ndb4  . } 10. Rd1 Rb8
{ As so often in this variation, this move comes in quite handy. First of all, the rook will never hang in any variation on the long diagonal. Secondly, we enable the move ...b5 to hang on to the c4-pawn. }
11. e4 Ncb4
{ This elegantly solves all of Black's problems. The knight attacks White’s queen on c2 and is headed to the d3-square, where it will be a thorn in White’s eye. }
12. Qb1 Nxc3
{ By trading on c3, we buy ourselves time to swiftly continue with our plan. }
13. bxc3 Nd3
{ Our knight has landed on d3, where it will always be extremely annoying for White. White should try to get rid of our strong knight by undermining the c4-pawn immediately. If White does not do so, we will follow up with ...b5 and we will be up a very clean pawn. }
14. Qb5 { White’s best move, getting rid of the c4-pawn immediately. } 14... c5
{ Since we do not have a good way to protect the c4-pawn, we should just continue by freeing up our pieces. }
15. Qxc4 { White finally regains the pawn. } 15... Nxc1
{ We had to give up our extra pawn, but now we get a different advantage in the form of the bishop pair. }
16. Raxc1 b5
{ White has managed to regain the pawn but we have the bishop pair and the potential to create an outside passed pawn on the queenside. Black has a good game here, as we have the bishop pair and the potential to create an outside passed pawn on the queenside.  After White’s queen moves, we can play ...Qc7, and potentially follow up with ...Rd8 and start expanding on the queenside with ...a5. Black was already for choice in the game Onischuk-Naroditsky, Saint Louis 2017. }
