[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Fianchetto Variation 4.g3"]
[Black "Fianchetto Variation 4.g3 − 6.Nf3 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3
{ The g3-System, which can also be referred to as the Romanishin Variation, turns the game into somewhat of a hybrid of the Catalan and the Nimzo. In this line, we will go for a quick ...d5 and ...dxc4. It will be difficult for White to get the pawn back, as their knight on c3 will always be in the way of a potential Qc2xc4. }
4... O-O
{ Playing  4...d5  first is fine as well.  5.Bg2  O-O  and we transpose to the main line. But not  5...dxc4??  as this loses a piece after  6.Qa4++-  . }
5. Bg2 d5
{ Our best approach is to place this pawn in the center and take on c4 quickly, as it will actually be difficult for White to get the pawn back. }
6. Nf3 dxc4
{ Since White has developed the bishop with g3 and Bg2, instead of with e3 and Bd3/e2, it is often a good idea to just take this pawn, as it is quite hard for White to get it back. }
7. O-O
{ If White plays  7.a3  we will just play  7...Bxc3  and transpose to the lines with the 6.a3 move order after  8.bxc3  . }
7... Nc6 { By eyeing the pawn on d4, we stop White from playing Ne5 and Qc2. }
8. a3 Be7 9. e4
{ In exchange for the sacrificed pawn, White gets the center and can try to use that to launch an attack on the kingside. At first, it seems that White's play is somewhat speculative but White's initiative on the kingside is actually going to be hard to deal with.   Less critical is  9.e3  , when  9...Na5  allows us to comfortably hold on to the extra pawn. A few games continued  10.Qe2  Rb8!  and we are ready to play ...b7-b5 next. Black is better. }
9... a6 { Planning ...b5 to hang on to the pawn on c4 and to prepare ...Bb7. }
10. Bf4
{ We will continue in the same fashion as against  10.Be3  , which we will see next. }
10... b5
{ Strengthening the pawn on c4, and vacating the b7-square for our bishop. }
11. Qe2
{ White's most popular move, freeing the d1-square for one of the rooks. }
11... Bb7
{ I would not suggest taking another pawn with  11...Nxd4  because after  12.Nxd4  Qxd4  13.Rad1  Qa7  14.e5  Nd5  15.Nxd5  exd5  16.Bxd5=∞  ,  White gets sufficient compensation for the pawn. }
12. Rad1
{ Since ...Nxd4 was an actual threat after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/2p1bppp/p1n1pn2/1p6/2pPPB2/P1N2NP1/1P2QPBP/R4RK1 b - - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Bb7  ,  White should defend the pawn on d4. }
12... Na5
{ Black is better, as we are up a pawn and White does not have quite sufficient compensation. Next, we are going to play ...Nb3 to exert more pressure on the pawn on d4, and ...c5 will be on our agenda as well. Furthermore, ...Re8 can be a useful improvement as well since the e-file will often open up after a potential d5 exd5 exd5. }
