13. Ne5
{ This was recently played by opening expert Sam Shankland. White wants to follow up here with f4 and g4-g5, and storm on the kingside. However, it will take some time before White fully gets their play on the kingside going, and in the meantime, we have plenty of ways to create counterplay or neutralize White's ideas on the kingside. }
13... Nb3 { Our best move, exerting more pressure on the d4-pawn. } 14. f4
{ White continues with their plan. } 14... Qe8
{ An excellent move. We vacate the d8-square for our rook. Furthermore, we often want to play ...Nd7 to trade off White's active knight on e5, so in the event of ...Nxe5 dxe5, our queen will never be hanging on d8. }
15. g4 Rd8 16. g5 Nd7
{ The position remains complicated but Black is certainly not on the worse side of things. Next, we can trade off White's active knight on e5, or try to push it back with ...f6. Either way, Black has a fine game here. }
