{ I like Ganguly's recommendation of  10...b5  in his Nimzo course. However, the positions remain extremely complicated after  11.h4  and I just wanted to recommend another variation to add something new. }
11. Qc2
{ 11.h4  loses its punch here, as we can meet it with  11...Nb3  12.Rb1  c5∓  and Black instantly takes over the initiative since we also have ...Ng4 in many variations. }
11... b5 12. Rad1
{ This has been played in three human games, so you are most likely to face this move. However, it is slightly inaccurate and Black gets an advantage here. }
12... Bb7 13. d5 Qe8
{ Keeping the e-file closed for now so White cannot use it to build an initiative. }
14. Bf4 Bd8 15. Rfe1 Nb3
{ White's pieces are active but there is no meaningful way to further improve the position or to create threats. In the meantime, we can slowly start crawling out with moves like ...h6 and ...Nd7. }
