[White "9) Fianchetto Variation 4.g3"]
[Black "Fianchetto Variation 4.g3 − 6.Nf3 #12"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3
{ The g3-System, which can also be referred to as the Romanishin Variation, turns the game into somewhat of a hybrid of the Catalan and the Nimzo. In this line, we will go for a quick ...d5 and ...dxc4. It will be difficult for White to get the pawn back, as their knight on c3 will always be in the way of a potential Qc2xc4. }
4... O-O
{ Playing  4...d5  first is fine as well.  5.Bg2  O-O  and we transpose to the main line. But not  5...dxc4??  as this loses a piece after  6.Qa4++-  . }
5. Bg2 d5
{ Our best approach is to place this pawn in the center and take on c4 quickly, as it will actually be difficult for White to get the pawn back. }
6. Nf3 dxc4
{ Since White has developed the bishop with g3 and Bg2, instead of with e3 and Bd3/e2, it is often a good idea to just take this pawn, as it is quite hard for White to get it back. }
7. O-O
{ If White plays  7.a3  we will just play  7...Bxc3  and transpose to the lines with the 6.a3 move order after  8.bxc3  . }
7... Nc6 { By eyeing the pawn on d4, we stop White from playing Ne5 and Qc2. }
8. a3 Be7 9. e4
{ In exchange for the sacrificed pawn, White gets the center and can try to use that to launch an attack on the kingside. At first, it seems that White's play is somewhat speculative but White's initiative on the kingside is actually going to be hard to deal with.   Less critical is  9.e3  , when  9...Na5  allows us to comfortably hold on to the extra pawn. A few games continued  10.Qe2  Rb8!  and we are ready to play ...b7-b5 next. Black is better. }
9... a6 10. Be3
{ Planning ...b5 to hang on to the pawn on c4 and to prepare ...Bb7. } 10...
Na5
{ I like Ganguly's recommendation of  10...b5  in his Nimzo course. However, the positions remain extremely complicated after  11.h4  and I just wanted to recommend another variation to add something new. }
11. Qc2
{ 11.h4  loses its punch here, as we can meet it with  11...Nb3  12.Rb1  c5∓  and Black instantly takes over the initiative since we also have ...Ng4 in many variations. }
11... b5 12. Ng5
{ This has only been played in one correspondence game. It is White's only move to hold the balance. }
12... e5
{ The easiest way to neutralize White's initiative and White actually has to play quite accurately to hold the balance.   12...Ng4  is also possible, but things get quite wild after  13.Nxh7  Kxh7  14.e5+  Kg8  15.Bxa8  c6  16.h3  Nxe3  17.fxe3  Bd7  18.Ne4∞  . }
13. dxe5 Ng4 14. Bf4
{ The only move for White not to lose. Otherwise, their position is in ruins. White sacrifices a piece but is going to get it back in the next couple of moves. }
14... Bxg5 15. Rad1 Bd7
{ The natural  15...Qe7  would not be ideal, as White can take over the initiative with  16.Nd5  Qd8  17.e6!  And not  17.Nf6+  which will be nicely met with  17...Bxf6  18.Rxd8  Bxd8  when Black is doing fine materially. After @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/2p2ppp/p7/np1NP1b1/2p1PBn1/P5P1/1PQ2PBP/3R1RK1 w - - 0 17@@EndFEN@@  17.e6  , the complications favor White, which is a scenario we shouldn't welcome. }
16. Bxg5 Qxg5 17. Rxd7 Rad8
{ Black has no problems whatsoever and it is actually White who needs to play somewhat accurately here to hold the balance. Note that after  18.Rxd8  Rxd8  ,  the pawn on e5 can't be rescued with  19.f4  due to  19...Qh6-+  and White is unable to parry  both threats on h2 and e3. }
