[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) Nimzo-Indian − Sidelines"]
[Black "Spielmann Variation 4.Qb3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qb3
{ The Spielmann Variation of the Nimzo. White's idea is to attack our bishop on b4 and simultaneously enable themselves to recapture with the queen on c3 to keep the pawn structure intact. However, the drawback is that the queen is somewhat misplaced on b3, compared to, say, c2. }
4... c5
{ Defending the bishop on b4 and putting pressure on White's center right away. }
5. dxc5 Nc6
{ Developing the knight and defending the bishop on b4. We can regain the pawn on c5 later. }
6. Nf3 Ne4
{ Such moves would not have been possible had White's queen been on c2. With this move, we threaten to cripple White's pawn structure with either ...Bxc3 or ...Nxc3. }
7. Bd2
{ White's only move to keep the pawn structure intact, but it does give up the dark-squared bishop, which we will gladly trade for our knight. }
7... Nxd2 8. Nxd2 Bxc5
{ Finally, we regain the pawn. Black has a completely fine game here, as we have already acquired the advantage of the bishop pair. We can continue our development with ...O-O and ...b6 and have nothing to worry about. }
9. e3 O-O 10. Be2 b6 11. O-O f5
{ Depriving White's knights of the e4-square and bringing ...f4 ideas in the position to activate our rook on f8 and to open up the diagonal for our dark-squared bishop. Black is somewhat better here, as we are going to play ...Bb7 next and White does not have any clear plans. }
*

