1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bg5
{ The Leningrad Variation. This is a rare guest at the GM level, and not without reason. Black immediately gets a comfortable position and White needs to be careful not to get worse. }
4... c5
{ Challenging White's center right away. Furthermore, this move enables ...Qa5, which exerts pressure on the c3-knight. }
5. Nf3
{ This move gives us the opportunity to transpose to one of the other lines, but we can be more ambitious. }
5... h6
{ Forcing White to make a decision with the dark-squared bishop.  5...O-O  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  O-O  5.Bg5  c5  . }
6. Bh4
{ This natural-looking reaction gives us the opportunity to immediately take over the initiative with a series of powerful moves. }
6... g5 { Breaking the pin on our f6-knight and attacking the bishop. } 7. Bg3
{ White's only move. } 7... g4
{ Attacking the f3-knight, which is playing a crucial role in keeping White's center together. }
8. Ne5 Ne4 { Threatening ...Nxc3. } 9. Rc1 d6
{ Pushing the knight back. White will be in trouble regardless of where the knight goes. }
10. Nxg4 { Grabbing the pawn does not solve White's problems. } 10... f5 11.
Ne3 Qf6
{ The combined threats of ...f4 and ...cxd4 are too much for White to handle. }
*

