1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bg5
{ The Leningrad Variation. This is a rare guest at the GM level, and not without reason. Black immediately gets a comfortable position and White needs to be careful not to get worse. }
4... c5
{ Challenging White's center right away. Furthermore, this move enables ...Qa5, which exerts pressure on the c3-knight. }
5. d5 d6 6. e3 Bxc3+
{ We should definitely take advantage of the opportunity to ruin White's pawn structure. }
7. bxc3 h6
{ Pushing White's bishop back a bit. Furthermore, we can later break the pin with a potential ...g5. }
8. Bh4 e5
{ Gaining more space in the center. Furthermore, our pawns nicely restrict the dark-squared bishop, as a lot of them are placed on dark squares. }
9. Qc2 Qe7
{ This move supports a potential ...e4, which gains more space and restricts White's pieces even further. Besides, we clear the d8-square − we sometimes want to play ...Kd8-c7. }
10. Nf3 g5
{ Breaking the pin on our f6-knight and pushing White's bishop back. } 11. Bg3
e4 { Gaining even more space, as now White's knight is being pushed back. } 12.
Nd2 Bf5
{ Developing the bishop and strengthening the pawn on e4. The big problem for White in this position is that a lot of their pieces lack serious prospects, and White has no effective pawn breaks. }
13. Be2
{ White would love to get the f4 break in. However,  13.f4  fails in this position.  13...Ng4∓  and  White has no comfortable way to protect the pawn on e3. }
13... Nbd7 14. h4 Bh7
{ This move might look somewhat odd, but it is the best way to deal with White's threat of hxg5. Now White never has any ideas of playing f4 since our bishop won't be hanging in the event of ...exf3. Next, I like the plan of ...Kf8-g7, followed by ...Bg6 and ...Ne5.   14...O-O?!  would not be the right way to deal with White's threat due to  15.hxg5  hxg5  16.f4⩲  and White gets a pleasant initiative, as now  16...exf3  is not possible due to  17.Qxf5  . }
*

