[White "11) Trompowsky Attack"]
[Black "Trompowsky Attack 2.Bg5 d5 3.Nd2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5
{ The Trompovsky. Often, White wants to follow up this move with Bxf6 to make us double our pawns with either ...gxf6 or ...exf6. Besides, White can also just continue development with e3 and moves like c3, Nd2, and Ngf3. }
2... d5
{ As a rule of thumb, if White does not play c4 early, we will place our pawn on d5, as placing a pawn in the center is rarely a bad idea.  Furthermore, since White is not exerting any pressure on our center, we can easily exert pressure on White's center with a quick ...c5. Besides, since White has brought out the bishop early to g5, a quick ...Qb6, attacking the pawn on b2, will often be effective. }
3. Nd2 Bf5
{ Here, I recommend this move because of its simplicity. We are just going to play a reversed London, with ...e6 coming next followed by ...Nbd7 and ...Be7.   3...c5  is possible as well, but the lines become quite complicated after  4.dxc5  e6  5.e4  Bxc5  and now both  6.Qe2  and  6.e5  lead to wild complications. Especially after 6.e5, the price of every move is very high. }
4. e3 e6
{ Solidifying the center − now we are always able to recapture with the queen of f6, so White can no longer give us doubled pawns. }
5. c4
{ After any other move, we are just going to play ...Nbd7 and ...Be7 after which we are completely fine. This move can pose some questions, so it will be good to know the proper response. }
5... Nbd7 6. Qb3 Be7
{ Instead of worrying about how to defend the b7-pawn, we are just going to sacrifice it. We will always get tremendous compensation if White will take due to our lead in development.   After  7.Qxb7  Rb8  8.Qxa7  Qc8  ,  threatening to trap the queen on a7 with ...Ra8,  9.Bf4  Rxb2  10.Ngf3  Bb4  , the engine already gives a decisive advantage for Black.  With ...Ne4 and ...O-O on the agenda, White's greed will be severely punished since Black has all the pieces mobilized for action. }
