[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) Trompowsky Attack"]
[Black "Trompowsky Attack 2.Bg5 d5 3.Bxf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5
{ The Trompovsky. Often, White wants to follow up this move with Bxf6 to make us double our pawns with either ...gxf6 or ...exf6. Besides, White can also just continue development with e3 and moves like c3, Nd2, and Ngf3. }
2... d5
{ As a rule of thumb, if White does not play c4 early, we will place our pawn on d5, as placing a pawn in the center is rarely a bad idea.  Furthermore, since White is not exerting any pressure on our center, we can easily exert pressure on White's center with a quick ...c5. Besides, since White has brought out the bishop early to g5, a quick ...Qb6, attacking the pawn on b2, will often be effective. }
3. Bxf6
{ White can also go for the trade on f6 right away, but this does not change much. }
3... gxf6
{ 3...exf6  is completely fine as well, as here we have not  played ...c5 yet, so we do not have to worry about our d5-pawn becoming isolated. However, I recommend the text, as I feel capturing towards the center is slightly more ambitious and we are quite likely to transpose to one of the other lines. }
4. c4
{ This is the only move that White can play if they do not want to transpose to one of the other lines. This is also what Aronian and Mamedyarov played in quite a few rapid and blitz games, so it is good to know how we should respond.   4.e3  c5  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3p2B1/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e3  c5  4.Bxf6  gxf6  , and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pp1p/5p2/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  c5  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3p2B1/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq d6 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  c5  4.Bxf6  gxf6  . }
4... e5
{ We should strike in the center right away, so we can continue our development swiftly. }
5. Nc3 { Developing the knight. However, this does sacrifice the pawn on c4. }
5... dxc4
{ We should take this pawn, as White does not have a good way to get it back. Furthermore, we are now also attacking the d4-pawn. }
6. Nf3 { The best way to defend the d4-pawn. } 6... exd4
{ The most straightforward way to make sure that White does not get an initiative going. }
7. Nxd4 Nc6
{ This move allows White to give us tripled pawns, but we will be able to exchange the queens and hang on to our extra pawns. }
8. Nxc6 Qxd1+
{ It is important to play this move first, as otherwise, White would be able to keep the queens on the board. }
9. Rxd1 bxc6
{ Despite our ugly pawn structure, we are doing quite well due to our extra pawn and bishop pair. Next, we are going to play ...Rb8 and ...Be6. }
