3... c5 4. dxc5 e6 5. e4
{ A tricky-looking move that was actually played in the old game Kramnik-Seirawan, Monte Carlo 1994. However, Black can take over the initiative with correct play. }
5... Bxc5
{ We should not be worried about White playing e5 and attacking the pinned knight on f6. }
6. e5 h6
{ The correct way to deal with White's threats.  6...Bxf2+?!  was played in the aforementioned game but after  7.Ke2±  , Black is losing a piece and does not get quite enough compensation. }
7. Bh4 g5
{ White's play has backfired, as we avoid losing material and now we will have our threats. }
