1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5
{ The Trompovsky. Often, White wants to follow up this move with Bxf6 to make us double our pawns with either ...gxf6 or ...exf6. Besides, White can also just continue development with e3 and moves like c3, Nd2, and Ngf3. }
2... d5
{ As a rule of thumb, if White does not play c4 early, we will place our pawn on d5, as placing a pawn in the center is rarely a bad idea.  Furthermore, since White is not exerting any pressure on our center, we can easily exert pressure on White's center with a quick ...c5. Besides, since White has brought out the bishop early to g5, a quick ...Qb6, attacking the pawn on b2, will often be effective. }
3. e3 c5 4. Bxf6 gxf6
{ I prefer this move over  4...exf6  .  If we were to take with the e-pawn, we would often end up with an isolated pawn on d5. }
5. dxc5 e6
{ I recommend this move, as it offers the easiest path to equality. White cannot prevent us from getting our pawn back, after which we will have a comfortable position.   5...Nc6  is possible as well, which leads to more complicated positions. }
6. Nf3 Bxc5 7. Be2
{ Somewhat counterintuitively, this is White's best attempt for an advantage. White just returns the pawn on c5 and calmly continues development. White will try to break in the center later with c4. }
7... Nc6 8. O-O O-O
{ Normally, castling kingside when the pawn structure is fractured is frowned upon, but here we are perfectly safe. White's pieces are in no position to reach our king. }
9. c4 d4
{ Once again, we do not want to let White take on d5 and ruin our pawn structure. But in this position, this move is more appropriate. }
10. exd4 Nxd4 11. Nc3 f5
{ Depriving White's knight of the e4-square and freeing up the f6-square for our queen, or potentially the bishop. Black has a good game, as we have the bishop pair. }
