[White "12) 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nc3"]
[Black "1.d4 Nf6 2.Nc3 d5 3.Nf3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3
{ By playing Nc3, White prepares the move 3.e4. As we don't want to give White the full center, we have to play ...d5. }
2... d5
{ Structurally speaking, White's knight is misplaced on c3. It stops White from exerting pressure on Black's center with c2-c4, and it also prevents White from strengthening their own center with c2-c3. However, White usually plays for quick development in this opening. }
3. Nf3
{ This move does not make much sense in conjunction with Nc3. The easiest way for us to continue is to just develop the light-squared bishop. }
3... Bf5
{ We are going to play a reversed London System with ...e6, ...Nbd7, ...c6, and ...Bd6 or ...Be7 coming next up. Black has a fine game, as White's knight on c3 is just misplaced and makes it difficult for White to come up with a meaningful plan. }
