[Black "Richter-Veresov Attack 3.Bg5 Nbd7 4.Qd3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3
{ By playing Nc3, White prepares the move 3.e4. As we don't want to give White the full center, we have to play ...d5. }
2... d5
{ Structurally speaking, White's knight is misplaced on c3. It stops White from exerting pressure on Black's center with c2-c4, and it also prevents White from strengthening their own center with c2-c3. However, White usually plays for quick development in this opening. }
3. Bg5
{ The Veresov Attack. White's idea is to develop quickly. However, since White's knight is misplaced on c3, we should not be worried about this since positionally, White's play is unsound and it is not easy for White to build up an attack.   Note that the usual Veresov move order is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.Bg5  , transposing to our repertoire. }
3... Nbd7
{ Now we can always meet Bxf6 with ...Nxf6, keeping our structure intact. } 4.
Qd3
{ Nakamura has played some games with this move almost a decade ago and it is recommended in the book The Richter-Veresov Attack: Qd3 Variation by Eric J. Fleischman. However, this is not a move we should be worried about, as it will give us good chances of getting an advantage. }
4... h6 { Forcing White to make a decision with the dark-squared bishop. } 5.
Bh4
{ The inclusion of ...h6 and Bh4 is generally in our favor. We should also not be worried about  5.Bxf6  Nxf6  since Black has a good game. We have the bishop pair, and we can follow up with ...g6, ...Bg7, ...O-O, and ...Bf5. }
5... c5 { We continue by challenging White's center. } 6. O-O-O
{ Castling queenside is extremely risky for White.   6.e4  has also been played in some games, but Black gets a good game here as well. Following  6...dxe4  7.Nxe4  Qa5+⩱  ,  White has no comfortable way of blocking the check. }
6... c4 7. Qf3 Qa5 { We are just going to steamroll White on the queenside. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nc3"]
[Black "Richter-Veresov Attack 3.Bg5 Nbd7 4.Qd3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3
{ By playing Nc3, White prepares the move 3.e4. As we don't want to give White the full center, we have to play ...d5. }
2... d5
{ Structurally speaking, White's knight is misplaced on c3. It stops White from exerting pressure on Black's center with c2-c4, and it also prevents White from strengthening their own center with c2-c3. However, White usually plays for quick development in this opening. }
3. Bg5
{ The Veresov Attack. White's idea is to develop quickly. However, since White's knight is misplaced on c3, we should not be worried about this since positionally, White's play is unsound and it is not easy for White to build up an attack.   Note that the usual Veresov move order is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.Bg5  , transposing to our repertoire. }
3... Nbd7
{ Now we can always meet Bxf6 with ...Nxf6, keeping our structure intact. } 4.
Qd3
{ Nakamura has played some games with this move almost a decade ago and it is recommended in the book The Richter-Veresov Attack: Qd3 Variation by Eric J. Fleischman. However, this is not a move we should be worried about, as it will give us good chances of getting an advantage. }
4... h6 { Forcing White to make a decision with the dark-squared bishop. } 5.
Bh4
{ The inclusion of ...h6 and Bh4 is generally in our favor. We should also not be worried about  5.Bxf6  Nxf6  since Black has a good game. We have the bishop pair, and we can follow up with ...g6, ...Bg7, ...O-O, and ...Bf5. }
5... c5 { We continue by challenging White's center. } 6. dxc5
{ White's most popular move.  6.e4  has also been played in some games, but Black gets a good game here as well. Following  6...dxe4  7.Nxe4  Qa5+⩱  ,  White has no comfortable way of blocking the check. }
6... e6
{ Strengthening the center first before recapturing on c5 since  6...Nxc5?!  7.Qb5+  forces us to make an awkward knight retreat. }
7. O-O-O
{ White's best continuation is to just return the pawn and continue development. White cannot hang on to the pawn, as  7.b4  a5-+  leads to a disaster. }
7... Nxc5 { Regaining the pawn and attacking White's queen at the same time. }
8. Qd4 { The best square for White's queen. } 8... Bd7
{ Black is already better. Next, we are going to play ...Be7 and ...Rc8. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nc3"]
[Black "Richter-Veresov Attack 3.Bg5 Nbd7 4.f3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3
{ By playing Nc3, White prepares the move 3.e4. As we don't want to give White the full center, we have to play ...d5. }
2... d5
{ Structurally speaking, White's knight is misplaced on c3. It stops White from exerting pressure on Black's center with c2-c4, and it also prevents White from strengthening their own center with c2-c3. However, White usually plays for quick development in this opening. }
3. Bg5
{ The Veresov Attack. White's idea is to develop quickly. However, since White's knight is misplaced on c3, we should not be worried about this since positionally, White's play is unsound and it is not easy for White to build up an attack.   Note that the usual Veresov move order is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.Bg5  , transposing to our repertoire. }
3... Nbd7
{ Now we can always meet Bxf6 with ...Nxf6, keeping our structure intact. } 4.
f3
{ White's idea is quite clear: to play e2-e4 quickly, taking the center, and after a potential e4-e5, our knight on f6 would not have a good square to go to. It is therefore important that we react quickly. }
4... h6 { Including ...h6 Bh4 will almost always be useful. } 5. Bxf6
{ White can decide on this move if they want to keep developing quickly. However, it does come at a high price, as now we get the advantage of the bishop pair. }
5... Nxf6 6. e4 e6 7. e5 Nd7
{ Black is already better. Next up, we will play ...c5 and we will have a good French, as we have the bishop pair and the fact that we have less space is not a problem at all since one of the knights has been exchanged. }
