1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3
{ By playing Nc3, White prepares the move 3.e4. As we don't want to give White the full center, we have to play ...d5. }
2... d5
{ Structurally speaking, White's knight is misplaced on c3. It stops White from exerting pressure on Black's center with c2-c4, and it also prevents White from strengthening their own center with c2-c3. However, White usually plays for quick development in this opening. }
3. Bg5
{ The Veresov Attack. White's idea is to develop quickly. However, since White's knight is misplaced on c3, we should not be worried about this since positionally, White's play is unsound and it is not easy for White to build up an attack.   Note that the usual Veresov move order is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.Bg5  , transposing to our repertoire. }
3... Nbd7
{ Now we can always meet Bxf6 with ...Nxf6, keeping our structure intact. } 4.
f3
{ White's idea is quite clear: to play e2-e4 quickly, taking the center, and after a potential e4-e5, our knight on f6 would not have a good square to go to. It is therefore important that we react quickly. }
4... h6 { Including ...h6 Bh4 will almost always be useful. } 5. Bh4 c5
