[Round "?"]
[White "12) 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nc3"]
[Black "Jobava London 3.Bf4 c5 4.e4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3
{ By playing Nc3, White prepares the move 3.e4. As we don't want to give White the full center, we have to play ...d5. }
2... d5
{ Structurally speaking, White's knight is misplaced on c3. It stops White from exerting pressure on Black's center with c2-c4, and it also prevents White from strengthening their own center with c2-c3. However, White usually plays for quick development in this opening. }
3. Bf4
{ The Jobava London. This has become a popular weapon in rapid and blitz games, as White has quick development and many traps. However, with accurate play, Black gets a good game. }
3... c5
{ Challenging White’s center right away. I like this move, as it is the most direct. }
4. e4
{ This is Hans Niemann's recommendation in his Chessable course on the Jobava London. It leads to direct complications, so it is important that we familiarize ourselves with the lines. }
4... cxd4 5. Qxd4 Nc6 6. Qa4
{ Oleksandr Bortnyk has played this line many times in blitz and with great success. However, it is somewhat dubious, and with accurate play, Black can get an advantage. }
6... dxe4 7. Nb5
{ Many players have simply been crushed in this position, as Black's response is far from obvious. It is therefore of utmost importance that you familiarize yourself with this variation if you want to meet the Jobava London with 3...c5. }
7... e5 8. Bxe5 Bc5
{ We simply develop the bishop and ignore White's threat of Nc7+. As far as I can tell, this move has not been played yet, which is a testament to how tricky this line is. }
9. Bxf6
{ White can try to avoid the massive complications with this move, but Black is already better. }
9... Qxf6
{ Recapturing the piece and eyeing the pawns on f2 and b2. White has to get the king out of the center as quickly as possible. }
10. Qxe4+ Be6 { Blocking the check and developing yet another piece. } 11.
O-O-O O-O
{ Black has tremendous compensation for the pawn, as we're ahead in development, we have the bishop pair, and the f2- and a2-pawns are hanging. }
*

