{ Many players have simply been crushed in this position, as Black's response is far from obvious. It is therefore of utmost importance that you familiarize yourself with this variation if you want to meet the Jobava London with 3...c5. }
7... e5 8. Bxe5 Bc5
{ We simply develop the bishop and ignore White's threat of Nc7+. As far as I can tell, this move has not been played yet, which is a testament to how tricky this line is. }
9. Nc7+ Kf8 10. Bg3
{ This is White's best move and also the one that requires a difficult response from Black. White has other moves as well, but Black is better after all of them.   In case of  10.Nxa8  Nxe5-+  ,  White is just completely lost, as the knight will get captured sooner or later and White is defenseless against the assault of Black's pieces. }
10... Bxf2+ 11. Kxf2 e3+
{ The most ambitious, setting the board on fire. Black can also make a draw here with  11...Qd2+  12.Be2  Ng4+  13.Kf1  Ne3+=  . }
12. Kxe3 Qe7+ 13. Kd2 Ne4+ 14. Qxe4
{ This move is actually possible and the complications are far from over. }
14... Qxe4 15. Re1 Qb4+ 16. Kc1 Bf5
{ As White was threatening mate with Re8, we have to give up the rook. } 17.
Nxa8 g6
{ White has more than enough material for the queen, as they have a rook, a bishop, and a knight. However, the king is lacking defenders and we are quickly going to create threats with moves like ...Qa4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nc3"]
[Black "Jobava London 3.Bf4 c5 4.e4 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3
{ By playing Nc3, White prepares the move 3.e4. As we don't want to give White the full center, we have to play ...d5. }
2... d5
{ Structurally speaking, White's knight is misplaced on c3. It stops White from exerting pressure on Black's center with c2-c4, and it also prevents White from strengthening their own center with c2-c3. However, White usually plays for quick development in this opening. }
3. Bf4
{ The Jobava London. This has become a popular weapon in rapid and blitz games, as White has quick development and many traps. However, with accurate play, Black gets a good game. }
3... c5
{ Challenging White’s center right away. I like this move, as it is the most direct. }
4. e4
{ This is Hans Niemann's recommendation in his Chessable course on the Jobava London. It leads to direct complications, so it is important that we familiarize ourselves with the lines. }
4... cxd4 5. Qxd4 Nc6 6. Bb5 Bd7
{ Essentially, forcing White to give up the bishop pair, which gives us a long-term asset. If we survive the next few moves, which we will, Black is likely to have good prospects. }
7. Bxc6 Bxc6 8. e5 Nd7 9. e6
{ White has to go for this pawn sacrifice. If White does not play this move, we will just continue with ...e6, and Black has a very comfortable French thanks to the bishop pair. }
9... fxe6 10. Nf3
{ The point behind White's play is that it is not easy for us to develop, as we currently cannot play ...g6, and ...e5 is also firmly under control. }
10... Qb6
{ Offering the queen trade in order to relieve some of White's grip on our position. }
11. Qd2 d4 { It is important to give the pawn back to liberate our pieces. }
12. Nxd4
{ 12.Qxd4  Bxf3=  and after  13.Qxb6  ,  either recapture followed by ...g6 is fine for Black. }
12... Bxg2 13. Rg1 e5
{ The only move not to get worse and actually keep our advantage. This counterpunch will often come in handy. }
14. Ndb5 exf4 15. Rxg2 Qe6+
{ White does not have a comfortable way to meet this check. } 16. Qe2 Qxe2+ 17.
Nxe2 Rc8
{ Stopping the fork and eyeing the pawn on c2. White is clearly worse in this endgame. }
*

