[Round "?"]
[White "12) 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nc3"]
[Black "Jobava London 3.Bf4 c5 4.e3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3
{ By playing Nc3, White prepares the move 3.e4. As we don't want to give White the full center, we have to play ...d5. }
2... d5
{ Structurally speaking, White's knight is misplaced on c3. It stops White from exerting pressure on Black's center with c2-c4, and it also prevents White from strengthening their own center with c2-c3. However, White usually plays for quick development in this opening. }
3. Bf4
{ The Jobava London. This has become a popular weapon in rapid and blitz games, as White has quick development and many traps. However, with accurate play, Black gets a good game. }
3... c5
{ Challenging White’s center right away. I like this move, as it is the most direct. }
4. e3
{ The calmer approach. White intends to recapture on d4 with the e-pawn and play a Carlsbad structure. }
4... cxd4 5. Nb5
{ Another tricky line that Oleksandr Bortnyk has deployed successfully in blitz and bullet. However, this will seriously backfire for White if we know what to do here. }
5... Qa5+
{ Since Black has no comfortable way of stopping Nc7+, we have to go for counterplay. White has no easy way of dealing with this check and things will get extremely complicated from here. }
6. b4
{ Blocking the check and attacking the queen. Black is forced to take.   6.c3  leads to the same thing after  6...dxc3  7.Nc7+  Kd8  8.b4  Qxb4  . }
6... Qxb4+ 7. c3
{ By sacrificing two pawns, White is buying time to collect the rook on a8. However, as we will soon see, Black's initiative is way too powerful. }
7... dxc3 8. Nc7+ Kd8 9. Nxa8 c2+ 10. Qd2 e5
{ Defending the queen with the bishop on f8 and this way Black is buying time to get the pieces in the game. }
11. Bxe5 Nc6 { Bringing out another piece with tempo. } 12. Bxf6+ gxf6 13. Rc1
Bf5
{ Despite the fact that Black is down a rook for only two pawns, we are completely winning due to our crushing attack and our mighty pawn on c2. Furthermore, White's knight on a8 is sooner or later going to be collected. An effective idea to continue our attack here will be to go ...Qb2/b1 and ...Bb4/a3. }
