[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3
{ By playing Nc3, White prepares the move 3.e4. As we don't want to give White the full center, we have to play ...d5. }
2... d5
{ Structurally speaking, White's knight is misplaced on c3. It stops White from exerting pressure on Black's center with c2-c4, and it also prevents White from strengthening their own center with c2-c3. However, White usually plays for quick development in this opening. }
3. Bf4
{ The Jobava London. This has become a popular weapon in rapid and blitz games, as White has quick development and many traps. However, with accurate play, Black gets a good game. }
3... c5
{ Challenging White’s center right away. I like this move, as it is the most direct. }
4. e3
{ The calmer approach. White intends to recapture on d4 with the e-pawn and play a Carlsbad structure. }
4... cxd4 5. exd4 a6
{ Stopping Nb5. Structurally speaking, Black is doing very well, as White's knight is misplaced on c3. White has to try to do something quickly, as otherwise, they are just worse if we get ...Nc6 and ...Bg4/f5 in. }
6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Ne5
{ The only critical move. After any other move, we develop our bishop to g4 or f5 and get a very comfortable position. White further activates the knight and also creates the positional threat of Nxc6, as ...bxc6 would be slightly detrimental to our pawn structure. }
7... Bd7
{ Therefore, we play this move so we can recapture with the bishop on c6 and keep our pawn structure intact. Again, if White were to play slowly here, Black is completely fine. So every top game from this position continued with g4. }
8. g3
{ This move has been played by the blitz specialists Tang, Naroditsky, and Niemann. However, we will get a comfortable game if we know the right continuation. }
8... e6 { Strengthening the center and continuing our development. } 9. Bg2
Nxe5
{ Trading off White's most active piece. It might seem somewhat odd to go for this move, as after  10.dxe5  ,  our knight will have to return to g8, but fortunately, we have a good way to bring it back into the game. }
10. dxe5
{ In case of  10.Bxe5  ,  we will get a comfortable game with  10...Bb4  ,  aiming to ruin White's pawn structure by trading on c3. Following  11.O-O  Bxc3  12.bxc3  Rc8  ,  Black has a comfortable game due to White's weak c3-pawn. }
10... Ng8
{ The only square that we can go to with our knight. At first sight, it seems that White should have an advantage due to the lead in development. However, the position is closed and White does not have any immediate breaks. This gives us the time to bring our knight back into the game with ...Ne7-g6.  If we manage to catch up in development, Black has good chances, as White's pawn on e5 can be a target. Furthermore, White's bishop on g2 is nicely blunted by our pawn on d5 and White's knight is also somewhat misplaced on c3. }
11. O-O Ne7 12. Ne2
{ Intending to break in the center with c4 and open up the h1-a8 diagonal for White's light-squared bishop. }
12... Qc7
{ I like the text more than  12...Rc8  , which is what I played against Andrew Tang in a Titled Tuesday.  Next up, we are going to play ...Ng6 to exert pressure on White's f4-bishop and e5-pawn. }
