[White "13) 1.d4 Sidelines"]
[Black "1.d4 Nf6 2.e3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. e3
{ Since White is delaying the move Nf3, they can opt to play a Stonewall system. The most important thing against Stonewall setups will be to develop our light-squared bishop, ideally to f5, but g4 is also not a bad square. }
2... d5 3. Bd3
{ Depriving our light-squared bishop of the f5-square. Fortunately, there are plenty of other ways to develop actively. }
3... c5
{ Since White is not exerting any pressure on our center, we will do so on White's center. Furthermore, we could potentially play ...c4 to push White's light-squared bishop off the b1-h7 diagonal. }
4. c3 Nc6 5. f4 Bg4
{ Again, against the Stonewall, we want to bring out our light-squared bishop before playing ...e6. Next up, we will play ...e6, followed by ...Bd6, and Black has an excellent game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) 1.d4 Sidelines"]
[Black "1.d4 Nf6 2.g4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. g4
{ This has been dubbed the Bronstein Gambit by some, and the Gibbins Weidenhagen Gambit by others. I would be surprised if you would see this being played in anything other than bullet games, but it is still nice to know a good response. }
2... Nxg4 { Of course, the best move is to take the pawn. } 3. e4
{ And this is the idea behind the sacrifice. White gets a second pawn in the center and attacks our knight on g4 right away. Fortunately for us, we can respond actively to White's play. }
3... d5 4. Be2 Nf6 5. e5 Ng8
{ I like this approach the best, as it is the easiest. } 6. c4
{ After any other move, we will bring out our bishop to f5, followed by ...e6, and Black will have a very good version of the Caro-Kann's Advanced variation. }
6... e6 7. Nc3 Ne7 8. Nf3 dxc4 9. Bxc4 Nd7
{ Next up, we will play ...Nb6, followed by ...Bd7-c6 and Black has an excellent game. Subsequently, we can opt for ...Qd7 and ...O-O-O. }
*

