[Black "1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6 3.Bf4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Bf4
{ This move has been played recently by a lot of strong grandmasters. The idea is to meet  3...Bb4+  with  4.Nd2  and later try to get the bishop pair without allowing Black to double White's pawns as we will often do in the Nimzo. }
3... d5
{ Placing a pawn in the center is rarely a bad idea, and this is no exception. }
4. e3 c5
{ If White allows us, we will play ...cxd4 and after exd4, we will eventually give White an isolated pawn on d4 by playing ...dxc4. If White will take on c5, we will recapture with the bishop followed by ...O-O, which gives us a good version of the Queen’s Gambit Declined, as we can play ...Bxc5 in one go, gaining a tempo. In either case, Black has nothing to worry about and has comfortable equality. }
