1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Bf4
{ This move has been played recently by a lot of strong grandmasters. The idea is to meet  3...Bb4+  with  4.Nd2  and later try to get the bishop pair without allowing Black to double White's pawns as we will often do in the Nimzo. }
3... d5
{ Placing a pawn in the center is rarely a bad idea, and this is no exception. }
4. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Usually, we would recapture with the pawn on d5, but here it’s good to recapture with the knight to gain a tempo, as we attack White’s bishop on f4. }
5. Bg3 c5 { Challenging White’s center right away. } 6. dxc5
{ Objectively, this might be White's best move, but it's quite toothless, as we get easy development and a symmetrical structure. }
6... Bxc5 7. Nd2
{ If White just continues development with  7.Nf3  ,  we will continue our development as well.  7...O-O   7...Qb6  is also possible, but things become quite sharp after  8.e4  .  8.Nbd2  @@StartBracket@@  8.e3  is inaccurate since here we do play  8...Qb6↑  , as b2 is actually quite awkward to defend.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp3ppp/4p3/2bn4/8/5NB1/PP1NPPPP/R2QKB1R b KQ - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nc6  transposes to the 7.Nd2 variation. }
7... Nc6
{ We will continue with ...O-O and ...f6 followed by ...e5, to neutralize White's bishop on g3, and Black has a comfortable position. }
