1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g4
{ When Mamedyarov played this move in the second round of the Tata Steel Masters against Esipenko, he shocked the chess world. However, this move is actually not as bad as it looks and some players have adopted it in their blitz games. There are many continuations that give Black a good game, but to me, the easiest seems to be: }
3... Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Bxd2+ 5. Qxd2
{ 5.Nxd2  is even worse since after  5...Nxg4  6.e4  , Black can still rely on  6...f5  and enjoy the extra material. Following  7.exf5  exf5  8.Qe2  Qe7  , White is simply a pawn down and has no compensation for it. If this hasn't convinced you yet, @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4p3/8/2PPP1n1/8/PP1N1P1P/R2QKBNR b KQkq e3 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Qh4  is an option as well. }
5... Nxg4
{ Now that White's queen is on d2, e2-e4 has lost its punch, as White will not be attacking the knight on g4. }
6. Nf3 f5
{ Making it difficult for White to get e2-e4 in, and this will also make it easier to defend our pawn on g7 with a potential ...Qe7. Next up, we are going to play ...Qe7, ...Nf6, and ...d6, and the onus will be on White to prove the compensation. Note that we are delaying ...O-O to keep the option of castling queenside alive. }
